\par \b Allocating Cleared Space\b0 
\par 
\par The function \f3 calloc\f0  allocates memory and clears it to zero. It is declared in \f3 stdlib.h\f0 .
\par -- Function: void * \b calloc\b0  (\i size_t count, size_t eltsize\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 This function allocates a block long enough to contain a vector of\i  count\i0  elements, each of size \i eltsize\i0 . Its contents are cleared to zero before \f3 calloc\f0  returns.
\par 
\par \pard You could define \f3 calloc\f0  as follows:
\par 
\par \f3      void *
\par      calloc (size_t count, size_t eltsize)
\par      \{
\par        size_t size = count * eltsize;
\par        void *value = malloc (size);
\par        if (value != 0)
\par          memset (value, 0, size);
\par        return value;
\par      \}
\par \f0 
\par But in general, it is not guaranteed that \f3 calloc\f0  calls\f3  malloc\f0  internally. Therefore, if an application provides its own\f3  malloc\f0 /\f3 realloc\f0 /\f3 free\f0  outside the C library, it should always define \f3 calloc\f0 , too.
\par 
