\par \b Argument Access Macros\b0 
\par 
\par Here are descriptions of the macros used to retrieve variable arguments. These macros are defined in the header file \f3 stdarg.h\f0 .
\par 
\par -- Data Type: \b va_list\b0 
\par 
\par \pard\li500 The type \f3 va_list\f0  is used for argument pointer variables.
\par 
\par \pard -- Macro: void \b va_start\b0  (\i va_list ap, last-required\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 This macro initializes the argument pointer variable \i ap\i0  to point to the first of the optional arguments of the current function;\i  last-required\i0  must be the last required argument to the function. 
\par \pard 
\par -- Macro: \i type\i0  \b va_arg\b0  (\i va_list ap, type\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 The \f3 va_arg\f0  macro returns the value of the next optional argument, and modifies the value of \i ap\i0  to point to the subsequent argument. Thus, successive uses of \f3 va_arg\f0  return successive optional arguments. 
\par 
\par The type of the value returned by \f3 va_arg\f0  is \i type\i0  as specified in the call. \i type\i0  must be a self-promoting type (not\f3  char\f0  or \f3 short int\f0  or \f3 float\f0 ) that matches the type of the actual argument.
\par 
\par \pard -- Macro: void \b va_end\b0  (\i va_list ap\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 This ends the use of \i ap\i0 . After a \f3 va_end\f0  call, further\f3  va_arg\f0  calls with the same \i ap\i0  may not work. You should invoke\f3  va_end\f0  before returning from the function in which \f3 va_start\f0  was invoked with the same \i ap\i0  argument. 
\par 
\par In th\f1 is \f0 C library, \f3 va_end\f0  does nothing, and you need not ever use it except for reasons of portability.
\par 
\par \pard Sometimes it is necessary to parse the list of parameters more than once or one wants to remember a certain position in the parameter list. To do this, one will have to make a copy of the current value of the argument. But \f3 va_list\f0  is an opaque type and one cannot necessarily assign the value of one variable of type \f3 va_list\f0  to another variable of the same type.
\par 
\par -- Macro: void \b __va_copy\b0  (\i va_list dest, va_list src\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 The \f3 va_copy\f0  macro allows copying of objects of type\f3  va_list\f0  even if this is not an integral type. The argument pointer in \i dest\i0  is initialized to point to the same argument as the pointer in \i src\i0 . 
\par \pard 
\par If you want to use \f3 va_copy\f0  you should always be prepared for the possibility that this macro will not be available. On architectures where a simple assignment is invalid, hopefully \f3 va_copy\f0  \i will\i0  be available, so one should always write something like this:
\par 
\par \f3      \{
\par        va_list ap, save;
\par        ...
\par      #ifdef va_copy
\par        va_copy (save, ap);
\par      #else
\par        save = ap;
\par      #endif
\par        ...
\par      \}
\par \f0 
