\viewkind4\uc1\pard\qc\lang1033\f0\fs24 Attribute Meanings 
\par \pard\ri100\fs18 Next:  Reading Attributes , Up:  File System Interface\fs2 
\par \pard\fs10 
\par \fs18 
\par \b The meaning of the File Attributes\b0 
\par 
\par When you read the attributes of a file, they come back in a structure called \f3 struct stat\f0 . This section describes the names of the attributes, their data types, and what they mean. For the functions to read the attributes of a file, see  Reading Attributes . 
\par 
\par The header file \f3 sys/stat.h\f0  declares all the symbols defined in this section
\par .
\par -- Data Type: \b struct stat\b0 
\par 
\par \pard\li500 The \f3 stat\f0  structure type is used to return information about the attributes of a file. It contains at least the following members:
\par 
\par \f3 mode_t st_mode\f0 
\par \f1            \f0 Specifies the mode of the file. This includes file type information  and the file permission bits 
\par \f3 ino_t st_ino\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 The file serial number, which distinguishes this file from all other files on the same device. 
\par \pard\li500\f3 dev_t st_dev\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 Identifies the device containing the file. The \f3 st_ino\f0  and\f3  st_dev\f0 , taken together, uniquely identify the file. The\f3  st_dev\f0  value is not necessarily consistent across reboots or system crashes, however. 
\par \pard\li500\f3 off_t st_size\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 This specifies the size of a regular file in bytes. For files that are really devices this field isn't usually meaningful. For symbolic links this specifies the length of the file name the link refers to. 
\par \pard\li500\f3 time_t st_atime\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 This is the last access time for the file.
\par \pard\li500\f3 time_t st_mtime\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 This is the time of the last modification to the contents of the file.
\par \pard\li500\f3 time_t st_ctime\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 This is the time of the last modification to the attributes of the file.
\par 
\par \pard Some of the file attributes have special data type names which exist specifically for those attributes. (They are all aliases for well-known integer types that you know and love.) These typedef names are defined in the header file \f3 sys/types.h\f0  as well as in \f3 sys/stat.h\f0 . Here is a list of them.
\par 
\par -- Data Type: \b mode_t\b0 
\par 
\par \pard\li500 This is an integer data type used to represent file modes. In the GNU system, this is equivalent to \f3 unsigned int\f0 .
\par 
\par \pard -- Data Type: \b ino_t\b0 
\par 
\par \pard\li500 This is an arithmetic data type used to represent file serial numbers. (In Unix jargon, these are sometimes called \i inode numbers\i0 .) In the GNU system, this type is equivalent to \f3 unsigned long int\f0 . 
\par 
\par If the source is compiled with \f3 _FILE_OFFSET_BITS == 64\f0  this type is transparently replaced by \f3 ino64_t\f0 .
\par \pard -- Data Type: \b dev_t\b0 
\par 
\par \pard\li500 This is an arithmetic data type used to represent file device numbers. In the GNU system, this is equivalent to \f3 int\f0 .
\par 
\par \pard\plain\f0

