\viewkind4\uc1\pard\qc\lang1033\f0\fs24 Broken-down Time 
\par \pard\fs18 Next:\f1  \f0   Formatting Calendar Time ,Up:  Calendar Time 
\par \fs10 
\par \pard\ri100\fs2 
\par \pard\fs10 
\par \fs18 
\par \b Broken-down Time\b0 
\par 
\par Calendar time is represented by the usual\f1  \f0 C library functions as an elapsed time since a fixed base calendar time. This is convenient for computation, but has no relation to the way people normally think of calendar time. By contrast, \i broken-down time\i0  is a binary representation of calendar time separated into year, month, day, and so on. Broken-down time values are not useful for calculations, but they are useful for printing human readable time information. 
\par 
\par A broken-down time value is always relative to a choice of time zone\f1 .\f0 
\par 
\par The symbols in this section are declared in the header file \f3 time.h\f0 .
\par -- Data Type: \b struct tm\b0 
\par 
\par \pard\li500 This is the data type used to represent a broken-down time. The structure contains at least the following members, which can appear in any order.
\par 
\par \f3 int tm_sec\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 This is the number of full seconds since the top of the minute (normally in the range \f3 0\f0  through \f3 59\f0 , but the actual upper limit is\f3  60\f0 , to allow for leap seconds if leap second support is available).
\par \pard\li500\f3 int tm_min\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 This is the number of full minutes since the top of the hour (in the range \f3 0\f0  through \f3 59\f0 ). 
\par \pard\li500\f3 int tm_hour\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 This is the number of full hours past midnight (in the range \f3 0\f0  through\f3  23\f0 ). 
\par \pard\li500\f3 int tm_mday\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 This is the ordinal day of the month (in the range \f3 1\f0  through \f3 31\f0 ). Watch out for this one! As the only ordinal number in the structure, it is inconsistent with the rest of the structure. 
\par \pard\li500\f3 int tm_mon\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 This is the number of full calendar months since the beginning of the year (in the range \f3 0\f0  through \f3 11\f0 ). Watch out for this one! People usually use ordinal numbers for month-of-year (where January = 1). 
\par \pard\li500\f3 int tm_year\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 This is the number of full calendar years since 1900. 
\par \pard\li500\f3 int tm_wday\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 This is the number of full days since Sunday (in the range \f3 0\f0  through\f3  6\f0 ). 
\par \pard\li500\f3 int tm_yday\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 This is the number of full days since the beginning of the year (in the range \f3 0\f0  through \f3 365\f0 ). 
\par \pard\li500\f3 int tm_isdst\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 This is a flag that indicates whether Daylight Saving Time is (or was, or will be) in effect at the time described. The value is positive if Daylight Saving Time is in effect, zero if it is not, and negative if the information is not available. 
\par 
\par \pard -- Function: struct tm * \b localtime\b0  (\i const time_t *time\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 The \f3 localtime\f0  function converts the simple time pointed to by\i  time\i0  to broken-down time representation, expressed relative to the user's specified time zone. 
\par 
\par The return value is a pointer to a static broken-down time structure, which might be overwritten by subsequent calls to \f3 ctime\f0 , \f3 gmtime\f0 , or \f3 localtime\f0 . (But no other library function overwrites the contents of this object.) 
\par 
\par The return value is the null pointer if \i time\i0  cannot be represented as a broken-down time; typically this is because the year cannot fit into an \f3 int\f0 . 
\par 
\par Calling \f3 localtime\f0  has one other effect: it sets the variable\f3  tzname\f0  with information about the current time zone. See  Time Zone Functions .
\par 
\par \pard -- Function: struct tm * \b gmtime\b0  (\i const time_t *time\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 This function is similar to \f3 localtime\f0 , except that the broken-down time is expressed as Coordinated Universal Time (UTC) (formerly called Greenwich Mean Time (GMT)) rather than relative to a local time zone.
\par 
\par \pard -- Function: time_t \b mktime\b0  (\i struct tm *brokentime\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 The \f3 mktime\f0  function is used to convert a broken-down time structure to a simple time representation. It also "normalizes" the contents of the broken-down time structure, by filling in the day of week and day of year based on the other date and time components. 
\par 
\par The \f3 mktime\f0  function ignores the specified contents of the\f3  tm_wday\f0  and \f3 tm_yday\f0  members of the broken-down time structure. It uses the values of the other components to determine the calendar time; it's permissible for these components to have unnormalized values outside their normal ranges. The last thing that\f3  mktime\f0  does is adjust the components of the \i brokentime\i0  structure (including the \f3 tm_wday\f0  and \f3 tm_yday\f0 ). 
\par 
\par If the specified broken-down time cannot be represented as a simple time,\f3  mktime\f0  returns a value of \f3 (time_t)(-1)\f0  and does not modify the contents of \i brokentime\i0 . 
\par 
\par Calling \f3 mktime\f0  also sets the variable \f3 tzname\f0  with information about the current time zone. See  Time Zone Functions .
\par 
\par \pard\plain\f0

