\par \pard\ri100\fs2 
\par \pard\fs10 
\par \fs18 
\par \b Character Input\b0 
\par 
\par This section describes functions for performing character-oriented input. These narrow streams functions are declared in the header file\f3  stdio.h\f0  and the wide character functions are declared in\f3  wchar.h\f0 . These functions return an \f3 int\f0  or \f3 wint_t\f0  value (for narrow and wide stream functions respectively) that is either a character of input, or the special value \f3 EOF\f0 /\f3 WEOF\f0  (usually -1). For the narrow stream functions it is important to store the result of these functions in a variable of type \f3 int\f0  instead of \f3 char\f0 , even when you plan to use it only as a character. Storing \f3 EOF\f0  in a\f3  char\f0  variable truncates its value to the size of a character, so that it is no longer distinguishable from the valid character `\f3 (char) -1\f0 '. So always use an \f3 int\f0  for the result of\f3  getc\f0  and friends, and check for \f3 EOF\f0  after the call; once you've verified that the result is not \f3 EOF\f0 , you can be sure that it will fit in a `\f3 char\f0 ' variable without loss of information.
\par \f1 
\par \f0 -- Function: int \b fgetc\b0  (\i FILE *stream\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 This function reads the next character as an \f3 unsigned char\f0  from the stream \i stream\i0  and returns its value, converted to an\f3  int\f0 . If an end-of-file condition or read error occurs,\f3  EOF\f0  is returned instead.
\par 
\par \pard -- Function: wint_t \b fgetwc\b0  (\i FILE *stream\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 This function reads the next wide character from the stream \i stream\i0  and returns its value. If an end-of-file condition or read error occurs, \f3 WEOF\f0  is returned instead.
\par 
\par \pard -- Function: int \b getc\b0  (\i FILE *stream\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 This is just like \f3 fgetc\f0 , except that it is permissible (and typical) for it to be implemented as a macro that evaluates the\i  stream\i0  argument more than once. \f3 getc\f0  is often highly optimized, so it is usually the best function to use to read a single character.
\par 
\par \pard -- Function: wint_t \b getwc\b0  (\i FILE *stream\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 This is just like \f3 fgetwc\f0 , except that it is permissible for it to be implemented as a macro that evaluates the \i stream\i0  argument more than once. \f3 getwc\f0  can be highly optimized, so it is usually the best function to use to read a single wide character.
\par 
\par \pard -- Function: int \b getchar\b0  (\i void\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 The \f3 getchar\f0  function is equivalent to \f3 getc\f0  with \f3 stdin\f0  as the value of the \i stream\i0  argument.
\par 
\par \pard -- Function: wint_t \b getwchar\b0  (\i void\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 The \f3 getwchar\f0  function is equivalent to \f3 getwc\f0  with \f3 stdin\f0  as the value of the \i stream\i0  argument.
\par 
\par \pard Here is an example of a function that does input using \f3 fgetc\f0 . It would work just as well using \f3 getc\f0  instead, or using\f3  getchar ()\f0  instead of \f3 fgetc (stdin)\f0 . The code would also work the same for the wide character stream functions.
\par 
\par \f3      int
\par      y_or_n_p (const char *question)
\par      \{
\par        fputs (question, stdout);
\par        while (1)
\par          \{
\par            int c, answer;
\par            /* Write a space to separate answer from question. */
\par            fputc (' ', stdout);
\par            /* Read the first character of the line.
\par               This should be the answer character, but might not be. */
\par            c = tolower (fgetc (stdin));
\par            answer = c;
\par            /* Discard rest of input line. */
\par            while (c != '\\n' && c != EOF)
\par              c = fgetc (stdin);
\par            /* Obey the answer if it was valid. */
\par            if (answer == 'y')
\par              return 1;
\par            if (answer == 'n')
\par              return 0;
\par            /* Answer was invalid: ask for valid answer. */
\par            fputs ("Please answer y or n:", stdout);
\par          \}
\par      \}
\par \f0 
\par \pard\plain\f0

