\par \pard\fs10 
\par \fs18 
\par \b Explicitly Checking Internal Consistency\b0 
\par 
\par When you're writing a program, it's often a good idea to put in checks at strategic places for "impossible" errors or violations of basic assumptions. These kinds of checks are helpful in debugging problems with the interfaces between different parts of the program, for example. 
\par 
\par The \f3 assert\f0  macro, defined in the header file \f3 assert.h\f0 , provides a convenient way to abort the program while printing a message about where in the program the error was detected. 
\par 
\par Once you think your program is debugged, you can disable the error checks performed by the \f3 assert\f0  macro by recompiling with the macro \f3 NDEBUG\f0  defined. This means you don't actually have to change the program source code to disable these checks. 
\par 
\par But disabling these consistency checks is undesirable unless they make the program significantly slower. All else being equal, more error checking is good no matter who is running the program. A wise user would rather have a program crash, visibly, than have it return nonsense without indicating anything might be wrong.
\par 
\par -- Macro: void \b assert\b0  (\i int expression\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 Verify the programmer's belief that \i expression\i0  is nonzero at this point in the program. 
\par 
\par If \f3 NDEBUG\f0  is not defined, \f3 assert\f0  tests the value of\i  expression\i0 . If it is false (zero), \f3 assert\f0  aborts the program (see  Aborting a Program ) after printing a message of the form: 
\par 
\par \f3           Assertion failed\f2  file(function:linenum) : expression\f3 .
\par     
\par \f0 on the standard error stream \f3 stderr\f0  (see  Standard Streams ). The filename and line number are taken from the C preprocessor macros\f3  __FILE__\f0  and \f3 __LINE__\f0  and specify where the call to\f3  assert\f0  was made. When using the\f1  \f0 C compiler, the name of the function which calls \f3 assert\f0  is taken from the built-in variable\f1  __func__.  When C99 mode is not enabled, the function name and following colon are not present.\f0 
\par 
\par If the preprocessor macro \f3 NDEBUG\f0  is defined before\f3  assert.h\f0  is included, the \f3 assert\f0  macro is defined to do absolutely nothing. 
\par 
\par \b Warning:\b0  Even the argument expression \i expression\i0  is not evaluated if \f3 NDEBUG\f0  is in effect. So never use \f3 assert\f0  with arguments that involve side effects. For example, \f3 assert (++i > 0);\f0  is a bad idea, because \f3 i\f0  will not be incremented if\f3  NDEBUG\f0  is defined.
\par 
\par \pard\b Usage note:\b0  The \f3 assert\f0  facility is designed for detecting \i internal inconsistency\i0 ; it is not suitable for reporting invalid input or improper usage by the \i user\i0  of the program. 
\par 
\par The information in the diagnostic messages printed by the \f3 assert\f0  macro is intended to help you, the programmer, track down the cause of a bug, but is not really useful for telling a user of your program why his or her input was invalid or why a command could not be carried out. What's more, your program should not abort when given invalid input, as \f3 assert\f0  would do--it should exit with nonzero status (see  Exit Status ) after printing its error messages, or perhaps read another command or move on to the next input file. 
\par 
\par See  Error Messages , for information on printing error messages for problems that \i do not\i0  represent bugs in the program.
\par 
\par \pard\plain\f0

