\par \b Creating Directories\b0 
\par 
\par Directories are created with the \f3 mkdir\f0  function. (There is also a shell command \f3 mkdir\f0  which does the same thing.)
\par -- Function: int \b mkdir\b0  (\i const char *filename, mode_t mode\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 The \f3 mkdir\f0  function creates a new, empty directory with name\i  filename\i0 . 
\par 
\par The argument \i mode\i0  specifies the file permissions for the new directory file. 
\par 
\par A return value of \f3 0\f0  indicates successful completion, and\f3  -1\f0  indicates failure. In addition to the usual file name syntax errors (see  File Name Errors ), the following \f3 errno\f0  error conditions are defined for this function:
\par 
\par \f3 EACCES\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 Write permission is denied for the parent directory in which the new directory is to be added. 
\par \pard\li500\f3 EEXIST\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 A file named \i filename\i0  already exists. 
\par \pard\li500\f3 ENOSPC\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 The file system doesn't have enough room to create the new directory. 
\par \pard\li500\f3 
\par \f0 To use this function, your program should include the header file\f3  \f2 dir\f3 .h\f0 .
