\par \pard\fs10 
\par \fs18 
\par \b Printing the Currency Symbol\b0 
\par 
\par These members of the \f3 struct lconv\f0  structure specify how to print the symbol to identify a monetary value--the international analog of `\f3 $\f0 ' for US dollars. 
\par 
\par Each country has two standard currency symbols. The \i local currency symbol\i0  is used commonly within the country, while the\i  international currency symbol\i0  is used internationally to refer to that country's currency when it is necessary to indicate the country unambiguously. 
\par 
\par For example, many countries use the dollar as their monetary unit, and when dealing with international currencies it's important to specify that one is dealing with (say) Canadian dollars instead of U.S. dollars or Australian dollars. But when the context is known to be Canada, there is no need to make this explicit--dollar amounts are implicitly assumed to be in Canadian dollars.
\par 
\par \f3 char *currency_symbol\f0 
\par \pard\li500 The local currency symbol for the selected locale. 
\par 
\par In the standard `\f3 C\f0 ' locale, this member has a value of \f3 ""\f0  (the empty string), meaning "unspecified". The ISO standard doesn't say what to do when you find this value; we recommend you simply print the empty string as you would print any other string pointed to by this variable. 
\par \pard\f3 char *int_curr_symbol\f0 
\par \pard\li500 The international currency symbol for the selected locale. 
\par 
\par The value of \f3 int_curr_symbol\f0  should normally consist of a three-letter abbreviation determined by the international standard\i  ISO 4217 Codes for the Representation of Currency and Funds\i0 , followed by a one-character separator (often a space). 
\par 
\par In the standard `\f3 C\f0 ' locale, this member has a value of \f3 ""\f0  (the empty string), meaning "unspecified". We recommend you simply print the empty string as you would print any other string pointed to by this variable. 
\par \pard\f3 char p_cs_precedes\f0 
\par \f3 char n_cs_precedes\f0 
\par \f3 char int_p_cs_precedes\f0 
\par \f3 char int_n_cs_precedes\f0 
\par \pard\li500 These members are \f3 1\f0  if the \f3 currency_symbol\f0  or\f3  int_curr_symbol\f0  strings should precede the value of a monetary amount, or \f3 0\f0  if the strings should follow the value. The\f3  p_cs_precedes\f0  and \f3 int_p_cs_precedes\f0  members apply to positive amounts (or zero), and the \f3 n_cs_precedes\f0  and\f3  int_n_cs_precedes\f0  members apply to negative amounts. 
\par 
\par In the standard `\f3 C\f0 ' locale, all of these members have a value of\f3  CHAR_MAX\f0 , meaning "unspecified". The ISO standard doesn't say what to do when you find this value. We recommend printing the currency symbol before the amount, which is right for most countries. In other words, treat all nonzero values alike in these members. 
\par 
\par The members with the \f3 int_\f0  prefix apply to the\f3  int_curr_symbol\f0  while the other two apply to\f3  currency_symbol\f0 . 
\par \pard\f3 char p_sep_by_space\f0 
\par \f3 char n_sep_by_space\f0 
\par \f3 char int_p_sep_by_space\f0 
\par \f3 char int_n_sep_by_space\f0 
\par \pard\li500 These members are \f3 1\f0  if a space should appear between the\f3  currency_symbol\f0  or \f3 int_curr_symbol\f0  strings and the amount, or \f3 0\f0  if no space should appear. The\f3  p_sep_by_space\f0  and \f3 int_p_sep_by_space\f0  members apply to positive amounts (or zero), and the \f3 n_sep_by_space\f0  and\f3  int_n_sep_by_space\f0  members apply to negative amounts. 
\par 
\par In the standard `\f3 C\f0 ' locale, all of these members have a value of\f3  CHAR_MAX\f0 , meaning "unspecified". The ISO standard doesn't say what you should do when you find this value; we suggest you treat it as 1 (print a space). In other words, treat all nonzero values alike in these members. 
\par 
\par The members with the \f3 int_\f0  prefix apply to the\f3  int_curr_symbol\f0  while the other two apply to\f3  currency_symbol\f0 . There is one specialty with the\f3  int_curr_symbol\f0 , though. Since all legal values contain a space at the end the string one either printf this space (if the currency symbol must appear in front and must be separated) or one has to avoid printing this character at all (especially when at the end of the string).
\par 
\par \pard\plain\f0

