\viewkind4\uc1\pard\qc\lang1033\f0\fs24 Deleting Files 
\par \pard\fs18 Next:  Renaming Files , Previous:\f1   Working Directory\f0 , Up:  File System Interface 
\par \fs10 
\par \pard\ri100\fs2 
\par \pard\fs10 
\par \fs18 
\par \b Deleting Files\b0 
\par 
\par You can delete a file with \f3 unlink\f0  or \f3 remove\f0 . 
\par 
\par Deletion actually deletes a file name. If this is the file's only name, then the file is deleted as well. 
\par 
\par -- Function: int \b unlink\b0  (\i const char *filename\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 The \f3 unlink\f0  function deletes the file name \i filename\i0 . If this is a file's sole name, the file itself is also deleted. (Actually, if any process has the file open when this happens, deletion is postponed until all processes have closed the file.) 
\par 
\par The function \f3 unlink\f0  is declared in the header file \f2 dir\f3 .h\f0 . 
\par 
\par This function returns \f3 0\f0  on successful completion, and \f3 -1\f0  on error. In addition to the usual file name errors (see  File Name Errors ), the following \f3 errno\f0  error conditions are defined for this function:
\par 
\par \f3 EACCES\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 Write permission is denied for the directory from which the file is to be removed, or the directory has the sticky bit set and you do not own the file. 
\par \pard\li500\f3 EBUSY\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 This error indicates that the file is being used by the system in such a way that it can't be unlinked. For example, you might see this error if the file name specifies the root directory or a mount point for a file system. 
\par \pard\li500\f3 ENOENT\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 The file name to be deleted doesn't exist. 
\par \pard\li500\f3 EPERM\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 On some systems \f3 unlink\f0  cannot be used to delete the name of a directory, or at least can only be used this way by a privileged user. To avoid such problems, use \f3 rmdir\f0  to delete directories. (In the GNU system \f3 unlink\f0  can never delete the name of a directory.) 
\par \pard\li500\f3 EROFS\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 The directory containing the file name to be deleted is on a read-only file system and can't be modified.
\par 
\par \pard -- Function: int \b rmdir\b0  (\i const char *filename\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 The \f3 rmdir\f0  function deletes a directory. The directory must be empty before it can be removed; in other words, it can only contain entries for \f3 .\f0  and \f3 ..\f0 . 
\par 
\par In most other respects, \f3 rmdir\f0  behaves like \f3 unlink\f0 . There are two additional \f3 errno\f0  error conditions defined for\f3  rmdir\f0 :
\par 
\par \f3 ENOTEMPTY\f0 
\par \f3 EEXIST\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 The directory to be deleted is not empty.
\par 
\par \pard\li500 These two error codes are synonymous; some systems use one, and some use the other. The GNU system always uses \f3 ENOTEMPTY\f0 . 
\par 
\par The prototype for this function is declared in the header file\f3  unistd.h\f0 .
\par 
\par \pard -- Function: int \b remove\b0  (\i const char *filename\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 This is the ISO C function to remove a file. It works like\f3  unlink\f0  for files and like \f3 rmdir\f0  for directories.\f3  remove\f0  is declared in \f3 stdio.h\f0 .
\par 
\par \pard\plain\f0

