\par \b Descriptors and Streams\b0 
\par 
\par Given an open file descriptor, you can create a stream for it with the\f3  fdopen\f0  function. \f1  \f0 Th\f1 is\f0  functions \f1 is\f0  declared in the header file \f3 stdio.h\f0 .
\par 
\par -- Function: FILE * \b fdopen\b0  (\i int filedes, const char *opentype\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 The \f3 fdopen\f0  function returns a new stream for the file descriptor\i  filedes\i0 . 
\par 
\par The \i opentype\i0  argument is interpreted in the same way as for the\f3  fopen\f0  function (see  Opening Streams ), except that the `\f3 b\f0 ' option is not permitted; this is because GNU makes no distinction between text and binary files. Also, \f3 "w"\f0  and\f3  "w+"\f0  do not cause truncation of the file; these have an effect only when opening a file, and in this case the file has already been opened. You must make sure that the \i opentype\i0  argument matches the actual mode of the open file descriptor. 
\par 
\par The return value is the new stream. If the stream cannot be created (for example, if the modes for the file indicated by the file descriptor do not permit the access specified by the \i opentype\i0  argument), a null pointer is returned instead. 
\par 
\par In some other systems, \f3 fdopen\f0  may fail to detect that the modes for file descriptor do not permit the access specified by\f3  opentype\f0 . The C library always checks for this.
\par 
\par \pard\plain\f0

