\viewkind4\uc1\pard\qc\lang1033\f0\fs24 Duplicating Descriptors 
\par \pard\fs18 Next:  File Status Flags , Previous:  Previous:  Duplicating Descriptors , Up:  Low-Level I/O 
\par \fs10 
\par 
\par \pard\ri100\fs2 
\par \pard\b\fs18 Duplicating Descriptors\b0 
\par 
\par You can \i duplicate\i0  a file descriptor, or allocate another file descriptor that refers to the same open file as the original. Duplicate descriptors share one file position and one set of file status flags (see  File Status Flags ), but each has its own set of file descriptor flags\f1 .\f0 
\par 
\par The major use of duplicating a file descriptor is to implement\i  redirection\i0  of input or output: that is, to change the file or pipe that a particular file descriptor corresponds to. 
\par 
\par \f1 T\f0 here are also convenient functions\f3  dup\f0  and \f3 dup2\f0  for duplicating descriptors. 
\par 
\par \f1 P\f0 rototypes for \f3 dup\f0  and \f3 dup2\f0  are in the header file\f3  \f2 io\f3 .h\f0 .
\par \f1 
\par \f0 -- Function: int \b dup\b0  (\i int old\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 This function copies descriptor \i old\i0  to the first available descriptor number (the first number not currently open).
\par 
\par \pard -- Function: int \b dup2\b0  (\i int old, int new\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 This function copies the descriptor \i old\i0  to descriptor number\i  new\i0 . 
\par 
\par If \i old\i0  is an invalid descriptor, then \f3 dup2\f0  does nothing; it does not close \i new\i0 . Otherwise, the new duplicate of \i old\i0  replaces any previous meaning of descriptor \i new\i0 , as if \i new\i0  were closed first. 
\par 
\par \pard Here is an example showing how to use \f3 dup2\f0  to do redirection. Typically, redirection of the standard streams (like \f3 stdin\f0 ) is done by a shell or shell-like program before calling one of the\f3  exec\f0  functions (see  Executing a File ) to execute a new program in a child process. When the new program is executed, it creates and initializes the standard streams to point to the corresponding file descriptors, before its \f3 main\f0  function is invoked. 
\par 
\par So, to redirect standard input to a file, the shell could do something like:
\par 
\par \f3          char *filename;
\par          char *program;
\par          int file;
\par          ...
\par          file = TEMP_FAILURE_RETRY (open (filename, O_RDONLY));
\par          dup2 (file, STDIN_FILENO);
\par          TEMP_FAILURE_RETRY (close (file));
\par          execv (program, NULL);
\par 
\par \f0 
\par \pard\plain\f0

