\viewkind4\uc1\pard\qc\lang1033\f0\fs24 Effects of Locale 
\par \pard\fs18 Next:  Choosing Locale , Up:  Locales 
\par \fs10 
\par \pard\ri100\fs2 
\par \pard\fs10 
\par \fs18 
\par \b What Effects a Locale Has\b0 
\par 
\par Each locale specifies conventions for several purposes, including the following:
\par 
\par \pard\li500\f2\'b7\f0  What multibyte character sequences are valid, and how they are interpreted (see  Character Set Handling ). 
\par \f2\'b7\f0  Classification of which characters in the local character set are considered alphabetic, and upper- and lower-case conversion conventions (see  Character Handling ). 
\par \f2\'b7\f0  The collating sequence for the local language and character set (see  Collation Functions ). 
\par \f2\'b7\f0  Formatting of numbers and currency amounts (see  General Numeric ). 
\par \f2\'b7\f0  Formatting of dates and times (see  Formatting Calendar Time ). 
\par \f2\'b7\f0  What language to use for user answers to yes-or-no questions (see  Yes-or-No Questions ). 
\par 
\par \pard Some aspects of adapting to the specified locale are handled automatically by the library subroutines. For example, all your program needs to do in order to use the collating sequence of the chosen locale is to use \f3 strcoll\f0  or \f3 strxfrm\f0  to compare strings. 
\par 
\par Other aspects of locales are beyond the comprehension of the library. For example, the library can't automatically translate your program's output messages into other languages. The only way you can support output in the user's favorite language is to program this more or less by hand. The C library provides functions to handle translations for multiple languages easily. 
\par 
\par This chapter discusses the mechanism by which you can modify the current locale. The effects of the current locale on specific library functions are discussed in more detail in the descriptions of those functions.
\par 
\par \pard\plain\f0

