\viewkind4\uc1\pard\qc\lang1033\f0\fs24 EOF and Errors 
\par \pard\fs18 Next:  Error Recovery , Previous:  Formatted Input , Up:  I/O on Streams 
\par \fs10 
\par \pard\ri100\fs2 
\par \pard\fs10 
\par \fs18 
\par \b End-Of-File and Errors\b0 
\par 
\par Many of the functions described in this chapter return the value of the macro \f3 EOF\f0  to indicate unsuccessful completion of the operation. Since \f3 EOF\f0  is used to report both end of file and random errors, it's often better to use the \f3 feof\f0  function to check explicitly for end of file and \f3 ferror\f0  to check for errors. These functions check indicators that are part of the internal state of the stream object, indicators set if the appropriate condition was detected by a previous I/O operation on that stream.
\par -- Macro: int \b EOF\b0 
\par 
\par \pard\li500 This macro is an integer value that is returned by a number of narrow stream functions to indicate an end-of-file condition, or some other error situation. With the GNU library, \f3 EOF\f0  is \f3 -1\f0 . In other libraries, its value may be some other negative number. 
\par 
\par This symbol is declared in \f3 stdio.h\f0 .
\par 
\par \pard -- Macro: int \b WEOF\b0 
\par 
\par \pard\li500 This macro is an integer value that is returned by a number of wide stream functions to indicate an end-of-file condition, or some other error situation. With the GNU library, \f3 WEOF\f0  is \f3 -1\f0 . In other libraries, its value may be some other negative number. 
\par 
\par This symbol is declared in \f3 wchar.h\f0 .
\par 
\par \pard -- Function: int \b feof\b0  (\i FILE *stream\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 The \f3 feof\f0  function returns nonzero if and only if the end-of-file indicator for the stream \i stream\i0  is set. 
\par 
\par This symbol is declared in \f3 stdio.h\f0 .
\par 
\par \pard -- Function: int \b ferror\b0  (\i FILE *stream\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 The \f3 ferror\f0  function returns nonzero if and only if the error indicator for the stream \i stream\i0  is set, indicating that an error has occurred on a previous operation on the stream. 
\par 
\par This symbol is declared in \f3 stdio.h\f0 .
\par 
\par \pard In addition to setting the error indicator associated with the stream, the functions that operate on streams also set \f3 errno\f0  in the same way as the corresponding low-level functions that operate on file descriptors. For example,  all of the \f3 errno\f0  error conditions defined for \f3 write\f0  are meaningful for functions\f1  \f0 such as \f3 fputc\f0 , \f3 printf\f0 , and \f3 fflush\f0 . For more information about the descriptor-level I/O functions, see  Low-Level I/O .
\par 
\par \pard\plain\f0

