\par \b File Name Errors\b0 
\par 
\par Functions that accept file name arguments usually detect these\f3  errno\f0  error conditions relating to the file name syntax or trouble finding the named file. These errors are referred to throughout this manual as the \i usual file name errors\i0 .
\par 
\par \f3 EACCES\f0 
\par \pard\li500 The process does not have search permission for a directory component of the file name. 
\par \pard\f3 ENAMETOOLONG\f0 
\par \pard\li500 This error is used when either the total length of a file name is greater than \f3 PATH_MAX\f0 , or when an individual file name component has a length greater than \f3 NAME_MAX\f0 .
\par 
\par In the GNU system, there is no imposed limit on overall file name length, but some file systems may place limits on the length of a component. 
\par \pard\f3 ENOENT\f0 
\par \pard\li480 This error is reported when a file referenced as a directory component in the file name doesn't exist\f1 .\f0 
\par \pard 
\par \f3 ENOTDIR\f0 
\par \pard\li500 A file that is referenced as a directory component in the file name exists, but it isn't a directory. 
\par \f3 
