\par \b Setting the File Position of a Descriptor\b0 
\par 
\par Just as you can set the file position of a stream with \f3 fseek\f0 , you can set the file position of a descriptor with \f3 lseek\f0 . This specifies the position in the file for the next \f3 read\f0  or\f3  write\f0  operation. See  File Positioning , for more information on the file position and what it means. 
\par 
\par To read the current file position value from a descriptor, use\f3  lseek (\i\f0 desc\i0\f3 , 0, SEEK_CUR)\f0 .
\par 
\par -- Function: off_t \b lseek\b0  (\i int filedes, off_t offset, int whence\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 The \f3 lseek\f0  function is used to change the file position of the file with descriptor \i filedes\i0 . 
\par 
\par The \i whence\i0  argument specifies how the \i offset\i0  should be interpreted, in the same way as for the \f3 fseek\f0  function, and it must be one of the symbolic constants \f3 SEEK_SET\f0 , \f3 SEEK_CUR\f0 , or\f3  SEEK_END\f0 .
\par 
\par \f3 SEEK_SET\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 Specifies that \i whence\i0  is a count of characters from the beginning of the file. 
\par \pard\li500\f3 SEEK_CUR\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 Specifies that \i whence\i0  is a count of characters from the current file position. This count may be positive or negative. 
\par \pard\li500\f3 SEEK_END\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 Specifies that \i whence\i0  is a count of characters from the end of the file. A negative count specifies a position within the current extent of the file; a positive count specifies a position past the current end. If you set the position past the current end, and actually write data, you will extend the file with zeros up to that position.
\par 
\par \pard\li500 The return value from \f3 lseek\f0  is normally the resulting file position, measured in bytes from the beginning of the file. You can use this feature together with \f3 SEEK_CUR\f0  to read the current file position. 
\par 
\par If you want to append to the file, setting the file position to the current end of file with \f3 SEEK_END\f0  is not sufficient. Another process may write more data after you seek but before you write, extending the file so the position you write onto clobbers their data. Instead, use the \f3 O_APPEND\f0  operating mode; see  Operating Modes . 
\par 
\par You can set the file position past the current end of the file. This does not by itself make the file longer; \f3 lseek\f0  never changes the file. But subsequent output at that position will extend the file. Characters between the previous end of file and the new position are filled with zeros. Extending the file in this way can create a "hole": the blocks of zeros are not actually allocated on disk, so the file takes up less space than it appears to; it is then called a "sparse file". If the file position cannot be changed, or the operation is in some way invalid, \f3 lseek\f0  returns a value of -1. The following\f3  errno\f0  error conditions are defined for this function:
\par 
\par \f3 EBADF\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 The \i filedes\i0  is not a valid file descriptor. 
\par \pard\li500\f3 EINVAL\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 The \i whence\i0  argument value is not valid, or the resulting file offset is not valid. A file offset is invalid. 
\par \pard\li500\f3 ESPIPE\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 The \i filedes\i0  corresponds to an object that cannot be positioned, such as a pipe, FIFO or terminal device. (POSIX.1 specifies this error only for pipes and FIFOs, but in the GNU system, you always get\f3  ESPIPE\f0  if the object is not seekable.)
\par \pard\li500 
\par \pard You can have multiple descriptors for the same file if you open the file more than once, or if you duplicate a descriptor with \f3 dup\f0 . Descriptors that come from separate calls to \f3 open\f0  have independent file positions; using \f3 lseek\f0  on one descriptor has no effect on the other. For example,
\par 
\par \f3      \{
\par        int d1, d2;
\par        char buf[4];
\par        d1 = open ("foo", O_RDONLY);
\par        d2 = open ("foo", O_RDONLY);
\par        lseek (d1, 1024, SEEK_SET);
\par        read (d2, buf, 4);
\par      \}
\par \f0 
\par will read the first four characters of the file \f3 foo\f0 . (The error-checking code necessary for a real program has been omitted here for brevity.) 
\par 
\par By contrast, descriptors made by duplication share a common file position with the original descriptor that was duplicated. Anything which alters the file position of one of the duplicates, including reading or writing data, affects all of them alike. Thus, for example,
\par 
\par \f3      \{
\par        int d1, d2, d3;
\par        char buf1[4], buf2[4];
\par        d1 = open ("foo", O_RDONLY);
\par        d2 = dup (d1);
\par        d3 = dup (d2);
\par        lseek (d3, 1024, SEEK_SET);
\par        read (d1, buf1, 4);
\par        read (d2, buf2, 4);
\par      \}
\par \f0 
\par will read four characters starting with the 1024'th character of\f3  foo\f0 , and then four more characters starting with the 1028'th character.
\par \pard\plain\f0

