\par \b File Status Flags\b0 
\par 
\par \i File status flags\i0  are used to specify attributes of the opening of a file. \f1 T\f0 he file status flags are shared by duplicated file descriptors resulting from a single opening of the file. The file status flags are specified with the \i flags\i0  argument to \f3 open\f0 ; see  Opening and Closing Files . 
\par 
\par File status flags fall into three categories, which are described in the following sections.
\par 
\par \pard\li500\f2\'b7\f0   Access Modes , specify what type of access is allowed to the file: reading, writing, or both. They are set by \f3 open\f0 , but cannot be changed. 
\par \f2\'b7\f0   Open-time Flags , control details of what \f3 open\f0  will do. These flags are not preserved after the \f3 open\f0  call. 
\par \f2\'b7\f0   Operating Modes , affect how operations such as \f3 read\f0  and\f3  write\f0  are done. They are set by \f3 open\f0 .
\par 
\par \pard The symbols in this section are defined in the header file\f3  fcntl.h\f0 .
