\par \b Floating Point Parameters\b0 
\par 
\par These macro definitions can be accessed by including the header file\f3  float.h\f0  in your program. 
\par 
\par Macro names starting with `\f3 FLT_\f0 ' refer to the \f3 float\f0  type, while names beginning with `\f3 DBL_\f0 ' refer to the \f3 double\f0  type and names beginning with `\f3 LDBL_\f0 ' refer to the \f3 long double\f0  type. 
\par 
\par Of these macros, only \f3 FLT_RADIX\f0  is guaranteed to be a constant expression. The other macros listed here cannot be reliably used in places that require constant expressions, such as `\f3 #if\f0 ' preprocessing directives or in the dimensions of static arrays. 
\par 
\par \f3 FLT_ROUNDS\f0 
\par \pard\li500 This value characterizes the rounding mode for floating point addition. The following values indicate standard rounding modes:
\par 
\par \f3 -1\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 The mode is indeterminable.
\par \pard\li500\f3 0\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 Rounding is towards zero.
\par \pard\li500\f3 1\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 Rounding is to the nearest number.
\par \pard\li500\f3 2\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 Rounding is towards positive infinity.
\par \pard\li500\f3 3\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 Rounding is towards negative infinity.
\par 
\par \pard\li500 Any other value represents a machine-dependent nonstandard rounding mode. 
\par 
\par On most machines, the value is \f3 1\f0 , in accordance with the IEEE standard for floating point. 
\par 
\par Here is a table showing how certain values round for each possible value of \f3 FLT_ROUNDS\f0 , if the other aspects of the representation match the IEEE single-precision standard. 
\par 
\par \f3                           0      1             2             3
\par            1.00000003    1.0    1.0           1.00000012    1.0
\par            1.00000007    1.0    1.00000012    1.00000012    1.0
\par           -1.00000003   -1.0   -1.0          -1.0          -1.00000012
\par           -1.00000007   -1.0   -1.00000012   -1.0          -1.00000012
\par      
\par \pard FLT_RADIX\f0 
\par \pard\li500 This is the value of the base, or radix, of the exponent representation. This is guaranteed to be a constant expression, unlike the other macros described in this section. The value is 2\f1 .\f3 
\par \pard FLT_MANT_DIG\f0 
\par \pard\li500 This is the number of base-\f3 FLT_RADIX\f0  digits in the floating point mantissa for the \f3 float\f0  data type. The following expression yields \f3 1.0\f0  (even though mathematically it should not) due to the limited number of mantissa digits: 
\par 
\par \f3           float radix = FLT_RADIX;
\par           
\par           1.0f + 1.0f / radix / radix / ... / radix
\par      
\par \f0 where \f3 radix\f0  appears \f3 FLT_MANT_DIG\f0  times.
\par \pard\f3 DBL_MANT_DIG\f0 
\par \f3 LDBL_MANT_DIG\f0 
\par \pard\li500 This is the number of base-\f3 FLT_RADIX\f0  digits in the floating point mantissa for the data types \f3 double\f0  and \f3 long double\f0 , respectively.
\par \pard\f3 FLT_DIG\f0 
\par \pard\li500 This is the number of decimal digits of precision for the \f3 float\f0  data type. Technically, if \i p\i0  and \i b\i0  are the precision and base (respectively) for the representation, then the decimal precision\i  q\i0  is the maximum number of decimal digits such that any floating point number with \i q\i0  base 10 digits can be rounded to a floating point number with \i p\i0  base \i b\i0  digits and back again, without change to the \i q\i0  decimal digits. 
\par 
\par The value of this macro is supposed to be at least \f3 6\f0 , to satisfy ISO C.
\par \pard\f3 DBL_DIG\f0 
\par \f3 LDBL_DIG\f0 
\par \pard\li500 These are similar to \f3 FLT_DIG\f0 , but for the data types\f3  double\f0  and \f3 long double\f0 , respectively. The values of these macros are supposed to be at least \f3 10\f0 .
\par \pard\f3 FLT_MIN_EXP\f0 
\par \pard\li500 This is the smallest possible exponent value for type \f3 float\f0 . More precisely, is the minimum negative integer such that the value\f3  FLT_RADIX\f0  raised to this power minus 1 can be represented as a normalized floating point number of type \f3 float\f0 .
\par \pard\f3 DBL_MIN_EXP\f0 
\par \f3 LDBL_MIN_EXP\f0 
\par \pard\li500 These are similar to \f3 FLT_MIN_EXP\f0 , but for the data types\f3  double\f0  and \f3 long double\f0 , respectively.
\par \pard\f3 FLT_MIN_10_EXP\f0 
\par \pard\li500 This is the minimum negative integer such that \f3 10\f0  raised to this power minus 1 can be represented as a normalized floating point number of type \f3 float\f0 . This is supposed to be \f3 -37\f0  or even less.
\par \pard\f3 DBL_MIN_10_EXP\f0 
\par \f3 LDBL_MIN_10_EXP\f0 
\par \pard\li500 These are similar to \f3 FLT_MIN_10_EXP\f0 , but for the data types\f3  double\f0  and \f3 long double\f0 , respectively.
\par \pard\f3 FLT_MAX_EXP\f0 
\par \pard\li500 This is the largest possible exponent value for type \f3 float\f0 . More precisely, this is the maximum positive integer such that value\f3  FLT_RADIX\f0  raised to this power minus 1 can be represented as a floating point number of type \f3 float\f0 .
\par \pard\f3 DBL_MAX_EXP\f0 
\par \f3 LDBL_MAX_EXP\f0 
\par \pard\li500 These are similar to \f3 FLT_MAX_EXP\f0 , but for the data types\f3  double\f0  and \f3 long double\f0 , respectively.
\par \pard\f3 FLT_MAX_10_EXP\f0 
\par \pard\li500 This is the maximum positive integer such that \f3 10\f0  raised to this power minus 1 can be represented as a normalized floating point number of type \f3 float\f0 . This is supposed to be at least \f3 37\f0 .
\par \pard\f3 DBL_MAX_10_EXP\f0 
\par \f3 LDBL_MAX_10_EXP\f0 
\par \pard\li500 These are similar to \f3 FLT_MAX_10_EXP\f0 , but for the data types\f3  double\f0  and \f3 long double\f0 , respectively.
\par \pard\f3 FLT_MAX\f0 
\par \pard\li500 The value of this macro is the maximum number representable in type\f3  float\f0 . It is supposed to be at least \f3 1E+37\f0 . The value has type \f3 float\f0 . 
\par 
\par The smallest representable number is \f3 - FLT_MAX\f0 .
\par \pard\f3 DBL_MAX\f0 
\par \f3 LDBL_MAX\f0 
\par \pard\li500 These are similar to \f3 FLT_MAX\f0 , but for the data types\f3  double\f0  and \f3 long double\f0 , respectively. The type of the macro's value is the same as the type it describes.
\par \pard\f3 FLT_MIN\f0 
\par \pard\li500 The value of this macro is the minimum normalized positive floating point number that is representable in type \f3 float\f0 . It is supposed to be no more than \f3 1E-37\f0 .
\par \pard\f3 DBL_MIN\f0 
\par \f3 LDBL_MIN\f0 
\par \pard\li500 These are similar to \f3 FLT_MIN\f0 , but for the data types\f3  double\f0  and \f3 long double\f0 , respectively. The type of the macro's value is the same as the type it describes.
\par \pard\f3 FLT_EPSILON\f0 
\par \pard\li500 This is the maximum positive floating point number of type \f3 float\f0  such that \f3 1.0 + FLT_EPSILON != 1.0\f0  is true. It's supposed to be no greater than \f3 1E-5\f0 .
\par \pard\f3 DBL_EPSILON\f0 
\par \f3 LDBL_EPSILON\f0 
\par \pard\li500 These are similar to \f3 FLT_EPSILON\f0 , but for the data types\f3  double\f0  and \f3 long double\f0 , respectively. The type of the macro's value is the same as the type it describes. The values are not supposed to be greater than \f3 1E-9\f0 .
\par 
