\par \b Flushing Buffers\b0 
\par 
\par \i Flushing\i0  output on a buffered stream means transmitting all accumulated characters to the file. There are many circumstances when buffered output on a stream is flushed automatically:
\par 
\par \pard\li500\f2\'b7\f0  When you try to do output and the output buffer is full. 
\par \f2\'b7\f0  When the stream is closed. See  Closing Streams . 
\par \f2\'b7\f0  When the program terminates by calling \f3 exit\f0 . See  Normal Termination . 
\par \f2\'b7\f0  When a newline is written, if the stream is line buffered. 
\par \f2\'b7\f0  Whenever an input operation on \i\f1 a console\i0\f0  stream actually reads data from its file.
\par 
\par \pard If you want to flush the buffered output at another time, call\f3  fflush\f0 , which is declared in the header file \f3 stdio.h\f0 .
\par 
\par -- Function: int \b fflush\b0  (\i FILE *stream\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 This function causes any buffered output on \i stream\i0  to be delivered to the file. If \i stream\i0  is a null pointer, then\f3  fflush\f0  causes buffered output on \i all\i0  open output streams to be flushed. 
\par 
\par This function returns \f3 EOF\f0  if a write error occurs, or zero otherwise.
\par \pard 
\par 
