\par \b Formatted Input Basics\b0 
\par 
\par Calls to \f3 scanf\f0  are superficially similar to calls to\f3  printf\f0  in that arbitrary arguments are read under the control of a template string. While the syntax of the conversion specifications in the template is very similar to that for \f3 printf\f0 , the interpretation of the template is oriented more towards free-format input and simple pattern matching, rather than fixed-field formatting. For example, most \f3 scanf\f0  conversions skip over any amount of "white space" (including spaces, tabs, and newlines) in the input file, and there is no concept of precision for the numeric input conversions as there is for the corresponding output conversions. Ordinarily, non-whitespace characters in the template are expected to match characters in the input stream exactly, but a matching failure is distinct from an input error on the stream. Another area of difference between \f3 scanf\f0  and \f3 printf\f0  is that you must remember to supply pointers rather than immediate values as the optional arguments to \f3 scanf\f0 ; the values that are read are stored in the objects that the pointers point to. Even experienced programmers tend to forget this occasionally, so if your program is getting strange errors that seem to be related to \f3 scanf\f0 , you might want to double-check this. 
\par 
\par When a \i matching failure\i0  occurs, \f3 scanf\f0  returns immediately, leaving the first non-matching character as the next character to be read from the stream. The normal return value from \f3 scanf\f0  is the number of values that were assigned, so you can use this to determine if a matching error happened before all the expected values were read. The \f3 scanf\f0  function is typically used for things like reading in the contents of tables. For example, here is a function that uses\f3  scanf\f0  to initialize an array of \f3 double\f0 :
\par 
\par \f3      void
\par      readarray (double *array, int n)
\par      \{
\par        int i;
\par        for (i=0; i<n; i++)
\par          if (scanf (" %lf", &(array[i])) != 1)
\par            invalid_input_error ();
\par      \}
\par \f0 
\par The formatted input functions are not used as frequently as the formatted output functions. Partly, this is because it takes some care to use them properly. Another reason is that it is difficult to recover from a matching error. 
\par 
