\par \b Formatted Input Functions\b0 
\par 
\par Here are the descriptions of the functions for performing formatted input. Prototypes for these functions are in the header file \f3 stdio.h\f0 .\f1 
\par \f0 
\par -- Function: int \b scanf\b0  (\i const char *template, ...\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 The \f3 scanf\f0  function reads formatted input from the stream\f3  stdin\f0  under the control of the template string \i template\i0 . The optional arguments are pointers to the places which receive the resulting values. 
\par 
\par The return value is normally the number of successful assignments. If an end-of-file condition is detected before any matches are performed, including matches against whitespace and literal characters in the template, then \f3 EOF\f0  is returned.
\par 
\par \pard -- Function: int \b wscanf\b0  (\i const wchar_t *template, ...\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 The \f3 wscanf\f0  function reads formatted input from the stream\f3  stdin\f0  under the control of the template string \i template\i0 . The optional arguments are pointers to the places which receive the resulting values. 
\par 
\par The return value is normally the number of successful assignments. If an end-of-file condition is detected before any matches are performed, including matches against whitespace and literal characters in the template, then \f3 WEOF\f0  is returned.
\par 
\par \pard -- Function: int \b fscanf\b0  (\i FILE *stream, const char *template, ...\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 This function is just like \f3 scanf\f0 , except that the input is read from the stream \i stream\i0  instead of \f3 stdin\f0 .
\par 
\par \pard -- Function: int \b fwscanf\b0  (\i FILE *stream, const wchar_t *template, ...\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 This function is just like \f3 wscanf\f0 , except that the input is read from the stream \i stream\i0  instead of \f3 stdin\f0 .
\par 
\par \pard -- Function: int \b sscanf\b0  (\i const char *s, const char *template, ...\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 This is like \f3 scanf\f0 , except that the characters are taken from the null-terminated string \i s\i0  instead of from a stream. Reaching the end of the string is treated as an end-of-file condition. 
\par 
\par The behavior of this function is undefined if copying takes place between objects that overlap--for example, if \i s\i0  is also given as an argument to receive a string read under control of the `\f3 %s\f0 ', `\f3 %S\f0 ', or `\f3 %[\f0 ' conversion.
\par 
\par \pard -- Function: int \b swscanf\b0  (\i const wchar_t *ws, const char *template, ...\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 This is like \f3 wscanf\f0 , except that the characters are taken from the null-terminated string \i ws\i0  instead of from a stream. Reaching the end of the string is treated as an end-of-file condition. 
