\par \b Formatting Calendar Time\b0 
\par 
\par The functions described in this section format calendar time values as strings. These functions are declared in the header file \f3 time.h\f0 .
\par 
\par -- Function: char * \b asctime\b0  (\i const struct tm *brokentime\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 The \f3 asctime\f0  function converts the broken-down time value that\i  brokentime\i0  points to into a string in a standard format: 
\par 
\par \f3           "Tue May 21 13:46:22 1991\\n"
\par      
\par \f0 The abbreviations for the days of week are: `\f3 Sun\f0 ', `\f3 Mon\f0 ', `\f3 Tue\f0 ', `\f3 Wed\f0 ', `\f3 Thu\f0 ', `\f3 Fri\f0 ', and `\f3 Sat\f0 '. 
\par 
\par The abbreviations for the months are: `\f3 Jan\f0 ', `\f3 Feb\f0 ', `\f3 Mar\f0 ', `\f3 Apr\f0 ', `\f3 May\f0 ', `\f3 Jun\f0 ', `\f3 Jul\f0 ', `\f3 Aug\f0 ', `\f3 Sep\f0 ', `\f3 Oct\f0 ', `\f3 Nov\f0 ', and `\f3 Dec\f0 '. 
\par 
\par The return value points to a statically allocated string, which might be overwritten by subsequent calls to \f3 asctime\f0  or \f3 ctime\f0 . (But no other library function overwrites the contents of this string.)
\par 
\par \pard -- Function: char * \b ctime\b0  (\i const time_t *time\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 The \f3 ctime\f0  function is similar to \f3 asctime\f0 , except that you specify the calendar time argument as a \f3 time_t\f0  simple time value rather than in broken-down local time format. It is equivalent to 
\par 
\par \f3           asctime (localtime (\i time\i0 ))
\par      
\par ctime\f0  sets the variable \f3 tzname\f0 , because \f3 localtime\f0  does so. See  Time Zone Functions .
\par 
\par \pard -- Function: size_t \b strftime\b0  (\i char *s, size_t size, const char *template, const struct tm *brokentime\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 This function is similar to the \f3 sprintf\f0  function (see  Formatted Input ), but the conversion specifications that can appear in the format template \i template\i0  are specialized for printing components of the date and time \i brokentime\i0  according to the locale currently specified for time conversion (see  Locales ). 
\par 
\par Ordinary characters appearing in the \i template\i0  are copied to the output string \i s\i0 ; this can include multibyte character sequences. Conversion specifiers are introduced by a `\f3 %\f0 ' character, followed by an optional flag which can be one of the following. These flags are all GNU extensions. The first three affect only the output of numbers:
\par 
\par \f3 _\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 The number is padded with spaces. 
\par \pard\li500\f3 -\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 The number is not padded at all. 
\par \pard\li500\f3 0\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 The number is padded with zeros even if the format specifies padding with spaces. 
\par \pard\li500\f3 ^\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 The output uses uppercase characters, but only if this is possible (see  Case Conversion ).
\par 
\par \pard\li500 The default action is to pad the number with zeros to keep it a constant width. Numbers that do not have a range indicated below are never padded, since there is no natural width for them. 
\par 
\par Following the flag an optional specification of the width is possible. This is specified in decimal notation. If the natural size of the output is of the field has less than the specified number of characters, the result is written right adjusted and space padded to the given size. 
\par 
\par An optional modifier can follow the optional flag and width specification. The modifiers, which are POSIX.2 extensions, are:
\par 
\par \f3 E\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 Use the locale's alternate representation for date and time. This modifier applies to the \f3 %c\f0 , \f3 %C\f0 , \f3 %x\f0 , \f3 %X\f0 ,\f3  %y\f0  and \f3 %Y\f0  format specifiers. In a Japanese locale, for example, \f3 %Ex\f0  might yield a date format based on the Japanese Emperors' reigns. 
\par \pard\li500\f3 O\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 Use the locale's alternate numeric symbols for numbers. This modifier applies only to numeric format specifiers.
\par 
\par \pard\li500 If the format supports the modifier but no alternate representation is available, it is ignored. 
\par 
\par The conversion specifier ends with a format specifier taken from the following list. The whole `\f3 %\f0 ' sequence is replaced in the output string as follows:
\par 
\par \f3 %a\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 The abbreviated weekday name according to the current locale. 
\par \pard\li500\f3 %A\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 The full weekday name according to the current locale. 
\par \pard\li500\f3 %b\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 The abbreviated month name according to the current locale. 
\par \pard\li500\f3 %B\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 The full month name according to the current locale. 
\par \pard\li500\f3 %c\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 The preferred calendar time representation for the current locale. 
\par \pard\li500\f3 %C\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 The century of the year. This is equivalent to the greatest integer not greater than the year divided by 100. 
\par 
\par This format is a POSIX.2 extension and also appears in ISO C99. 
\par \pard\li500\f3 %d\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 The day of the month as a decimal number (range \f3 01\f0  through \f3 31\f0 ). 
\par \pard\li500\f3 %D\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 The date using the format \f3 %m/%d/%y\f0 . 
\par 
\par This format is a POSIX.2 extension and also appears in ISO C99. 
\par \pard\li500\f3 %e\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 The day of the month like with \f3 %d\f0 , but padded with blank (range\f3  1\f0  through \f3 31\f0 ). 
\par 
\par This format is a POSIX.2 extension and also appears in ISO C99. 
\par \pard\li500\f3 %F\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 The date using the format \f3 %Y-%m-%d\f0 . This is the form specified in the ISO 8601 standard and is the preferred form for all uses. 
\par 
\par This format is a ISO C99 extension. 
\par \pard\li500\f3 %g\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 The year corresponding to the ISO week number, but without the century (range \f3 00\f0  through \f3 99\f0 ). This has the same format and value as \f3 %y\f0 , except that if the ISO week number (see \f3 %V\f0 ) belongs to the previous or next year, that year is used instead. 
\par 
\par This format was introduced in ISO C99. 
\par \pard\li500\f3 %G\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 The year corresponding to the ISO week number. This has the same format and value as \f3 %Y\f0 , except that if the ISO week number (see\f3  %V\f0 ) belongs to the previous or next year, that year is used instead. 
\par 
\par This format was introduced in ISO C99 but was previously available as a GNU extension. 
\par \pard\li500\f3 %h\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 The abbreviated month name according to the current locale. The action is the same as for \f3 %b\f0 . 
\par 
\par This format is a POSIX.2 extension and also appears in ISO C99. 
\par \pard\li500\f3 %H\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 The hour as a decimal number, using a 24-hour clock (range \f3 00\f0  through\f3  23\f0 ). 
\par \pard\li500\f3 %I\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 The hour as a decimal number, using a 12-hour clock (range \f3 01\f0  through\f3  12\f0 ). 
\par \pard\li500\f3 %j\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 The day of the year as a decimal number (range \f3 001\f0  through \f3 366\f0 ). 
\par \pard\li500\f3 %k\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 The hour as a decimal number, using a 24-hour clock like \f3 %H\f0 , but padded with blank (range \f3 0\f0  through \f3 23\f0 ). 
\par 
\par This format is a GNU extension. 
\par \pard\li500\f3 %l\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 The hour as a decimal number, using a 12-hour clock like \f3 %I\f0 , but padded with blank (range \f3 1\f0  through \f3 12\f0 ). 
\par 
\par This format is a GNU extension. 
\par \pard\li500\f3 %m\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 The month as a decimal number (range \f3 01\f0  through \f3 12\f0 ). 
\par \pard\li500\f3 %M\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 The minute as a decimal number (range \f3 00\f0  through \f3 59\f0 ). 
\par \pard\li500\f3 %n\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 A single `\f3\\n\f0 ' (newline) character. 
\par 
\par This format is a POSIX.2 extension and also appears in ISO C99. 
\par \pard\li500\f3 %p\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 Either `\f3 AM\f0 ' or `\f3 PM\f0 ', according to the given time value; or the corresponding strings for the current locale. Noon is treated as `\f3 PM\f0 ' and midnight as `\f3 AM\f0 '. 
\par \pard\li500\f3 %P\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 Either `\f3 am\f0 ' or `\f3 pm\f0 ', according to the given time value; or the corresponding strings for the current locale, printed in lowercase characters. Noon is treated as `\f3 pm\f0 ' and midnight as `\f3 am\f0 '. 
\par 
\par This format was introduced in ISO C99 but was previously available as a GNU extension. 
\par \pard\li500\f3 %r\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 The complete calendar time using the AM/PM format of the current locale. 
\par 
\par This format is a POSIX.2 extension and also appears in ISO C99. 
\par \pard\li500\f3 %R\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 The hour and minute in decimal numbers using the format \f3 %H:%M\f0 . 
\par 
\par This format was introduced in ISO C99 but was previously available as a GNU extension. 
\par \pard\li500\f3 %s\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 The number of seconds since the epoch, i.e., since 1970-01-01 00:00:00 UTC. Leap seconds are not counted unless leap second support is available. 
\par 
\par This format is a GNU extension. 
\par \pard\li500\f3 %S\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 The seconds as a decimal number (range \f3 00\f0  through \f3 60\f0 ). 
\par \pard\li500\f3 %t\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 A single `\f3\\t\f0 ' (tabulator) character. 
\par 
\par This format is a POSIX.2 extension and also appears in ISO C99. 
\par \pard\li500\f3 %T\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 The time of day using decimal numbers using the format \f3 %H:%M:%S\f0 . 
\par 
\par This format is a POSIX.2 extension. 
\par \pard\li500\f3 %u\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 The day of the week as a decimal number (range \f3 1\f0  through\f3  7\f0 ), Monday being \f3 1\f0 . 
\par 
\par This format is a POSIX.2 extension and also appears in ISO C99. 
\par \pard\li500\f3 %U\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 The week number of the current year as a decimal number (range \f3 00\f0  through \f3 53\f0 ), starting with the first Sunday as the first day of the first week. Days preceding the first Sunday in the year are considered to be in week \f3 00\f0 . 
\par \pard\li500\f3 %V\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 The ISO 8601:1988 week number as a decimal number (range \f3 01\f0  through \f3 53\f0 ). ISO weeks start with Monday and end with Sunday. Week \f3 01\f0  of a year is the first week which has the majority of its days in that year; this is equivalent to the week containing the year's first Thursday, and it is also equivalent to the week containing January 4. Week \f3 01\f0  of a year can contain days from the previous year. The week before week \f3 01\f0  of a year is the last week (\f3 52\f0  or\f3  53\f0 ) of the previous year even if it contains days from the new year. 
\par 
\par This format is a POSIX.2 extension and also appears in ISO C99. 
\par \pard\li500\f3 %w\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 The day of the week as a decimal number (range \f3 0\f0  through\f3  6\f0 ), Sunday being \f3 0\f0 . 
\par \pard\li500\f3 %W\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 The week number of the current year as a decimal number (range \f3 00\f0  through \f3 53\f0 ), starting with the first Monday as the first day of the first week. All days preceding the first Monday in the year are considered to be in week \f3 00\f0 . 
\par \pard\li500\f3 %x\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 The preferred date representation for the current locale. 
\par \pard\li500\f3 %X\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 The preferred time of day representation for the current locale. 
\par \pard\li500\f3 %y\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 The year without a century as a decimal number (range \f3 00\f0  through\f3  99\f0 ). This is equivalent to the year modulo 100. 
\par \pard\li500\f3 %Y\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 The year as a decimal number, using the Gregorian calendar. Years before the year \f3 1\f0  are numbered \f3 0\f0 , \f3 -1\f0 , and so on. 
\par \pard\li500\f3 %z\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 RFC 822/ISO 8601:1988 style numeric time zone (e.g.,\f3  -0600\f0  or \f3 +0100\f0 ), or nothing if no time zone is determinable. 
\par 
\par This format was introduced in ISO C99 but was previously available as a GNU extension. 
\par 
\par A full RFC 822 timestamp is generated by the format `\f3 "%a, %d %b %Y %H:%M:%S %z"\f0 ' (or the equivalent `\f3 "%a, %d %b %Y %T %z"\f0 '). 
\par \pard\li500\f3 %Z\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 The time zone abbreviation (empty if the time zone can't be determined). 
\par \pard\li500\f3 %%\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 A literal `\f3 %\f0 ' character.
\par 
\par \pard\li500 The \i size\i0  parameter can be used to specify the maximum number of characters to be stored in the array \i s\i0 , including the terminating null character. If the formatted time requires more than \i size\i0  characters, \f3 strftime\f0  returns zero and the contents of the array\i  s\i0  are undefined. Otherwise the return value indicates the number of characters placed in the array \i s\i0 , not including the terminating null character. 
\par 
\par \i Warning:\i0  This convention for the return value which is prescribed in ISO C can lead to problems in some situations. For certain format strings and certain locales the output really can be the empty string and this cannot be discovered by testing the return value only. E.g., in most locales the AM/PM time format is not supported (most of the world uses the 24 hour time representation). In such locales\f3  "%p"\f0  will return the empty string, i.e., the return value is zero. To detect situations like this something similar to the following code should be used: 
\par 
\par \f3           buf[0] = '\\1';
\par           len = strftime (buf, bufsize, format, tp);
\par           if (len == 0 && buf[0] != '\\0')
\par             \{
\par               /* Something went wrong in the strftime call.  */
\par               ...
\par             \}
\par      
\par \f0 If \i s\i0  is a null pointer, \f3 strftime\f0  does not actually write anything, but instead returns the number of characters it would have written. 
\par 
\par According to POSIX.1 every call to \f3 strftime\f0  implies a call to\f3  tzset\f0 . So the contents of the environment variable \f3 TZ\f0  is examined before any output is produced. 
\par 
\par For an example of \f3 strftime\f0 , see  Time Functions Example .
\par 
\par \pard -- Function: size_t \b wcsftime\b0  (\i wchar_t *s, size_t size, const wchar_t *template, const struct tm *brokentime\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 The \f3 wcsftime\f0  function is equivalent to the \f3 strftime\f0  function with the difference that it operates on wide character strings. The buffer where the result is stored, pointed to by \i s\i0 , must be an array of wide characters. The parameter \i size\i0  which specifies the size of the output buffer gives the number of wide character, not the number of bytes. 
\par 
\par Also the format string \i template\i0  is a wide character string. Since all characters needed to specify the format string are in the basic character set it is portably possible to write format strings in the C source code using the \f3 L"..."\f0  notation. The parameter\i  brokentime\i0  has the same meaning as in the \f3 strftime\f0  call. 
\par 
\par The \f3 wcsftime\f0  function supports the same flags, modifiers, and format specifiers as the \f3 strftime\f0  function. 
\par 
\par The return value of \f3 wcsftime\f0  is the number of wide characters stored in \f3 s\f0 . When more characters would have to be written than can be placed in the buffer \i s\i0  the return value is zero, with the same problems indicated in the \f3 strftime\f0  documentation.
\par 
\par \pard\plain\f0

