\par \fs18 
\par \b\f1 C99 \f0 Variable-Size Arrays\b0 
\par 
\par In C\f1 99\f0 , you can replace most uses of \f3 alloca\f0  with an array of variable size. Here is how \f3 open2\f0  would look then:
\par 
\par \f3      int open2 (char *str1, char *str2, int flags, int mode)
\par      \{
\par        char name[strlen (str1) + strlen (str2) + 1];
\par        stpcpy (stpcpy (name, str1), str2);
\par        return open (name, flags, mode);
\par      \}
\par \f0 
\par But \f3 alloca\f0  is not always equivalent to a variable-sized array, for several reasons:
\par 
\par \pard\li500\f2\'b7\f0  A variable size array's space is freed at the end of the scope of the name of the array. The space allocated with \f3 alloca\f0  remains until the end of the function. 
\par \f2\'b7\f0  It is possible to use \f3 alloca\f0  within a loop, allocating an additional block on each iteration. This is impossible with variable-sized arrays.
\par 
\par \pard\b Note:\b0  If you mix use of \f3 alloca\f0  and variable-sized arrays within one function, exiting a scope in which a variable-sized array was declared frees all blocks allocated with \f3 alloca\f0  during the execution of that scope.
\par 
\par \pard\plain\f0

