\par \b Important Data Types\b0 
\par 
\par The result of subtracting two pointers in C is always an integer, but the precise data type varies from C compiler to C compiler. Likewise, the data type of the result of \f3 sizeof\f0  also varies between compilers. ISO defines standard aliases for these two types, so you can refer to them in a portable fashion. They are defined in the header file\f3  stddef.h\f0 .
\par 
\par -- Data Type: \b ptrdiff_t\b0 
\par 
\par \pard\li500 This is the signed integer type of the result of subtracting two pointers. For example, with the declaration \f3 char *p1, *p2;\f0 , the expression \f3 p2 - p1\f0  is of type \f3 ptrdiff_t\f0 . This will probably be one of the standard signed integer types (\f3 short int\f0 , \f3 int\f0  or \f3 long int\f0 ), but might be a nonstandard type that exists only for this purpose.
\par 
\par \pard -- Data Type: \b size_t\b0 
\par 
\par \pard\li500 This is an unsigned integer type used to represent the sizes of objects. The result of the \f3 sizeof\f0  operator is of this type, and functions such as \f3 malloc\f0  (see  Unconstrained Allocation ) and\f3  memcpy\f0  (see  Copying and Concatenation ) accept arguments of this type to specify object sizes. 
\par 
\par \b Usage Note:\b0  \f3 size_t\f0  is the preferred way to declare any arguments or variables that hold the size of an object.
\par 
\par \pard In th\f1 is\f0  system \f3 size_t\f0  is equivalent to \f3 unsigned int\f0 .
\par 
\par \b Compatibility Note:\b0  Implementations of C before the advent of ISO C generally used \f3 unsigned int\f0  for representing object sizes and \f3 int\f0  for pointer subtraction results. They did not necessarily define either \f3 size_t\f0  or \f3 ptrdiff_t\f0 . Unix systems did define \f3 size_t\f0 , in \f3 sys/types.h\f0 , but the definition was usually a signed type.
\par 
\par \pard\plain\f0

