\par \b Input and Output Primitives\b0 
\par 
\par This section describes the functions for performing primitive input and output operations on file descriptors: \f3 read\f0 , \f3 write\f0 , and\f3  lseek\f0 . These functions are declared in the header file\f3  unistd.h\f0 .
\par 
\par -- Function: \f1 int\f0  \b read\b0  (\i int filedes, void *buffer, size_t size\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 The \f3 read\f0  function reads up to \i size\i0  bytes from the file with descriptor \i filedes\i0 , storing the results in the \i buffer\i0 . (This is not necessarily a character string, and no terminating null character is added.) 
\par 
\par The return value is the number of bytes actually read. This might be less than \i size\i0 ; for example, if there aren't that many bytes left in the file or if there aren't that many bytes immediately available. The exact behavior depends on what kind of file it is. Note that reading less than \i size\i0  bytes is not an error. 
\par 
\par A value of zero indicates end-of-file (except if the value of the\i  size\i0  argument is also zero). This is not considered an error. If you keep calling \f3 read\f0  while at end-of-file, it will keep returning zero and doing nothing else. 
\par 
\par If \f3 read\f0  returns at least one character, there is no way you can tell whether end-of-file was reached. But if you did reach the end, the next read will return zero. 
\par 
\par In case of an error, \f3 read\f0  returns -1. The following\f3  errno\f0  error conditions are defined for this function:
\par 
\par \f3 EAGAIN\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 Normally, when no input is immediately available, \f3 read\f0  waits for some input. But if the \f3 O_NONBLOCK\f0  flag is set for the file (see  File Status Flags ), \f3 read\f0  returns immediately without reading any data, and reports this error. 
\par 
\par \b Compatibility Note:\b0  Most versions of BSD Unix use a different error code for this: \f3 EWOULDBLOCK\f0 . In the GNU library,\f3  EWOULDBLOCK\f0  is an alias for \f3 EAGAIN\f0 , so it doesn't matter which name you use. 
\par 
\par On some systems, reading a large amount of data from a character special file can also fail with \f3 EAGAIN\f0  if the kernel cannot find enough physical memory to lock down the user's pages. This is limited to devices that transfer with direct memory access into the user's memory, which means it does not include terminals, since they always use separate buffers inside the kernel. This problem never happens in the GNU system. 
\par 
\par Any condition that could result in \f3 EAGAIN\f0  can instead result in a successful \f3 read\f0  which returns fewer bytes than requested. Calling \f3 read\f0  again immediately would result in \f3 EAGAIN\f0 . 
\par \pard\li500\f3 EBADF\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 The \i filedes\i0  argument is not a valid file descriptor, or is not open for reading. 
\par \pard\li500\f3 EINTR\f0 
\par \pard\li1000\f3 read\f0  was interrupted by a signal while it was waiting for input. See  Interrupted Primitives . A signal will not necessary cause\f3  read\f0  to return \f3 EINTR\f0 ; it may instead result in a successful \f3 read\f0  which returns fewer bytes than requested. 
\par \pard\li500\f3 EIO\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 For many devices, and for disk files, this error code indicates a hardware error. 
\par 
\par \f3 EIO\f0  also occurs when a background process tries to read from the controlling terminal, and the normal action of stopping the process by sending it a \f3 SIGTTIN\f0  signal isn't working. This might happen if the signal is being blocked or ignored, or because the process group is orphaned. See  Job Control , for more information about job control, and  Signal Handling , for information about signals.
\par 
\par \pard -- Function: int \b write\b0  (\i int filedes, const void *buffer, size_t size\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 The \f3 write\f0  function writes up to \i size\i0  bytes from\i  buffer\i0  to the file with descriptor \i filedes\i0 . The data in\i  buffer\i0  is not necessarily a character string and a null character is output like any other character. 
\par 
\par The return value is the number of bytes actually written. This may be\i  size\i0 , but can always be smaller. Your program should always call\f3  write\f0  in a loop, iterating until all the data is written. 
\par 
\par Once \f3 write\f0  returns, the data is enqueued to be written and can be read back right away, but it is not necessarily written out to permanent storage immediately. You can use \f3 fsync\f0  when you need to be sure your data has been permanently stored before continuing. (It is more efficient for the system to batch up consecutive writes and do them all at once when convenient. Normally they will always be written to disk within a minute or less.) Modern systems provide another function\f3  fdatasync\f0  which guarantees integrity only for the file data and is therefore faster. You can use the \f3 O_FSYNC\f0  open mode to make \f3 write\f0  always store the data to disk before returning; see  Operating Modes . 
\par 
\par In the case of an error, \f3 write\f0  returns -1. The following\f3  errno\f0  error conditions are defined for this function:
\par 
\par \f3 EAGAIN\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 Normally, \f3 write\f0  blocks until the write operation is complete. But if the \f3 O_NONBLOCK\f0  flag is set for the file (see  Control Operations ), it returns immediately without writing any data and reports this error. An example of a situation that might cause the process to block on output is writing to a terminal device that supports flow control, where output has been suspended by receipt of a STOP character. 
\par 
\par \b Compatibility Note:\b0  Most versions of BSD Unix use a different error code for this: \f3 EWOULDBLOCK\f0 . In the GNU library,\f3  EWOULDBLOCK\f0  is an alias for \f3 EAGAIN\f0 , so it doesn't matter which name you use. 
\par 
\par On some systems, writing a large amount of data from a character special file can also fail with \f3 EAGAIN\f0  if the kernel cannot find enough physical memory to lock down the user's pages. This is limited to devices that transfer with direct memory access into the user's memory, which means it does not include terminals, since they always use separate buffers inside the kernel. This problem does not arise in the GNU system. 
\par \pard\li500\f3 EBADF\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 The \i filedes\i0  argument is not a valid file descriptor, or is not open for writing. 
\par \pard\li500\f3 EFBIG\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 The size of the file would become larger than the implementation can support. 
\par \pard\li500\f3 EINTR\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 The \f3 write\f0  operation was interrupted by a signal while it was blocked waiting for completion. A signal will not necessarily cause\f3  write\f0  to return \f3 EINTR\f0 ; it may instead result in a successful \f3 write\f0  which writes fewer bytes than requested. See  Interrupted Primitives . 
\par \pard\li500\f3 EIO\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 For many devices, and for disk files, this error code indicates a hardware error. 
\par \pard\li500\f3 ENOSPC\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 The device containing the file is full. 
\par \pard\li500\f3 EPIPE\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 This error is returned when you try to write to a pipe or FIFO that isn't open for reading by any process. When this happens, a \f3 SIGPIPE\f0  signal is also sent to the process; see  Signal Handling .
\par \pard\plain\f0

