\par \b Miscellaneous FP arithmetic functions\b0 
\par 
\par The functions in this section perform miscellaneous but common operations that are awkward to express with C operators. On some processors these functions can use special machine instructions to perform these operations faster than the equivalent C code.
\par 
\par -- Function: double \b fmin\b0  (\i double x, double y\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 -- Function: float \b fminf\b0  (\i float x, float y\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li1000 -- Function: long double \b fminl\b0  (\i long double x, long double y\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li1500 The \f3 fmin\f0  function returns the lesser of the two values \i x\i0  and \i y\i0 . It is similar to the expression 
\par 
\par \f3           ((x) < (y) ? (x) : (y))
\par      
\par \f0 except that \i x\i0  and \i y\i0  are only evaluated once. 
\par 
\par If an argument is NaN, the other argument is returned. If both arguments are NaN, NaN is returned.
\par 
\par \pard -- Function: double \b fmax\b0  (\i double x, double y\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 -- Function: float \b fmaxf\b0  (\i float x, float y\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li1000 -- Function: long double \b fmaxl\b0  (\i long double x, long double y\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li1500 The \f3 fmax\f0  function returns the greater of the two values \i x\i0  and \i y\i0 . 
\par 
\par If an argument is NaN, the other argument is returned. If both arguments are NaN, NaN is returned.
\par 
\par \pard -- Function: double \b fdim\b0  (\i double x, double y\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 -- Function: float \b fdimf\b0  (\i float x, float y\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li1000 -- Function: long double \b fdiml\b0  (\i long double x, long double y\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li1500 The \f3 fdim\f0  function returns the positive difference between\i  x\i0  and \i y\i0 . The positive difference is \i x\i0  -\i  y\i0  if \i x\i0  is greater than \i y\i0 , and 0 otherwise. 
\par 
\par If \i x\i0 , \i y\i0 , or both are NaN, NaN is returned.
\par 
\par \pard -- Function: double \b fma\b0  (\i double x, double y, double z\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 -- Function: float \b fmaf\b0  (\i float x, float y, float z\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li1000 -- Function: long double \b fmal\b0  (\i long double x, long double y, long double z\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li1500 The \f3 fma\f0  function performs floating-point multiply-add. This is the operation (\i x\i0  \f1 *\f0  \i y\i0 ) + \i z\i0 , but the intermediate result is not rounded to the destination type. This can sometimes improve the precision of a calculation. 
\par 
\par This function was introduced because some processors have a special instruction to perform multiply-add. The C compiler cannot use it directly, because the expression `\f3 x*y + z\f0 ' is defined to round the intermediate result. \f3 fma\f0  lets you choose when you want to round only once. 
\par 
\par On processors which do not implement multiply-add in hardware,\f3  fma\f0  can be very slow since it must avoid intermediate rounding.\f3  math.h\f0  defines the symbols \f3 FP_FAST_FMA\f0 ,\f3  FP_FAST_FMAF\f0 , and \f3 FP_FAST_FMAL\f0  when the corresponding version of \f3 fma\f0  is no slower than the expression `\f3 x*y + z\f0 '.
\par 
