\par \b Details of Non-Local Exits\b0 
\par 
\par Here are the details on the functions and data structures used for performing non-local exits. These facilities are declared in\f3  setjmp.h\f0 .
\par 
\par -- Data Type: \b jmp_buf\b0 
\par 
\par \pard\li500 Objects of type \f3 jmp_buf\f0  hold the state information to be restored by a non-local exit. The contents of a \f3 jmp_buf\f0  identify a specific place to return to.
\par 
\par \pard -- Macro: int \b setjmp\b0  (\i jmp_buf state\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 When called normally, \f3 setjmp\f0  stores information about the execution state of the program in \i state\i0  and returns zero. If\f3  longjmp\f0  is later used to perform a non-local exit to this\i  state\i0 , \f3 setjmp\f0  returns a nonzero value.
\par 
\par \pard -- Function: void \b longjmp\b0  (\i jmp_buf state, int value\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 This function restores current execution to the state saved in\i  state\i0 , and continues execution from the call to \f3 setjmp\f0  that established that return point. Returning from \f3 setjmp\f0  by means of\f3  longjmp\f0  returns the \i value\i0  argument that was passed to\f3  longjmp\f0 , rather than \f3 0\f0 . (But if \i value\i0  is given as\f3  0\f0 , \f3 setjmp\f0  returns \f3 1\f0 ).
\par 
\par \pard There are a lot of obscure but important restrictions on the use of\f3  setjmp\f0  and \f3 longjmp\f0 . Most of these restrictions are present because non-local exits require a fair amount of magic on the part of the C compiler and can interact with other parts of the language in strange ways. 
\par 
\par The \f3 setjmp\f0  function is actually a macro without an actual function definition, so you shouldn't try to `\f3 #undef\f0 ' it or take its address. In addition, calls to \f3 setjmp\f0  are safe in only the following contexts:
\par 
\par \pard\li500\f2\'b7\f0  As the test expression of a selection or iteration statement (such as `\f3 if\f0 ', `\f3 switch\f0 ', or `\f3 while\f0 '). 
\par \f2\'b7\f0  As one operand of a equality or comparison operator that appears as the test expression of a selection or iteration statement. The other operand must be an integer constant expression. 
\par \f2\'b7\f0  As the operand of a unary `\f3 !\f0 ' operator, that appears as the test expression of a selection or iteration statement. 
\par \f2\'b7\f0  By itself as an expression statement.
\par 
\par \pard Return points are valid only during the dynamic extent of the function that called \f3 setjmp\f0  to establish them. If you \f3 longjmp\f0  to a return point that was established in a function that has already returned, unpredictable and disastrous things are likely to happen. 
\par 
\par You should use a nonzero \i value\i0  argument to \f3 longjmp\f0 . While\f3  longjmp\f0  refuses to pass back a zero argument as the return value from \f3 setjmp\f0 , this is intended as a safety net against accidental misuse and is not really good programming style. 
\par 
\par When you perform a non-local exit, accessible objects generally retain whatever values they had at the time \f3 longjmp\f0  was called. The exception is that the values of automatic variables local to the function containing the \f3 setjmp\f0  call that have been changed since the call to \f3 setjmp\f0  are indeterminate, unless you have declared them \f3 volatile\f0 .
\par 
\par \pard\plain\f0

