\par \b Non-reentrant Conversion of Single Characters\b0 
\par 
\par -- Function: int \b mbtowc\b0  (\i wchar_t *restrict result, const char *restrict string, size_t size\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 The \f3 mbtowc\f0  ("multibyte to wide character") function when called with non-null \i string\i0  converts the first multibyte character beginning at \i string\i0  to its corresponding wide character code. It stores the result in \f3 *\i\f0 result\i0 . 
\par 
\par \f3 mbtowc\f0  never examines more than \i size\i0  bytes. (The idea is to supply for \i size\i0  the number of bytes of data you have in hand.) 
\par 
\par \f3 mbtowc\f0  with non-null \i string\i0  distinguishes three possibilities: the first \i size\i0  bytes at \i string\i0  start with valid multibyte characters, they start with an invalid byte sequence or just part of a character, or \i string\i0  points to an empty string (a null character). 
\par 
\par For a valid multibyte character, \f3 mbtowc\f0  converts it to a wide character and stores that in \f3 *\i\f0 result\i0 , and returns the number of bytes in that character (always at least 1 and never more than \i size\i0 ). 
\par 
\par For an invalid byte sequence, \f3 mbtowc\f0  returns -1. For an empty string, it returns 0, also storing \f3 '\\0'\f0  in\f3  *\i\f0 result\i0 . 
\par 
\par If the multibyte character code uses shift characters, then\f3  mbtowc\f0  maintains and updates a shift state as it scans. If you call \f3 mbtowc\f0  with a null pointer for \i string\i0 , that initializes the shift state to its standard initial value. It also returns nonzero if the multibyte character code in use actually has a shift state. See  Shift State .
\par 
\par \pard -- Function: int \b wctomb\b0  (\i char *string, wchar_t wchar\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 The \f3 wctomb\f0  ("wide character to multibyte") function converts the wide character code \i wchar\i0  to its corresponding multibyte character sequence, and stores the result in bytes starting at\i  string\i0 . At most \f3 MB_CUR_MAX\f0  characters are stored. 
\par 
\par \f3 wctomb\f0  with non-null \i string\i0  distinguishes three possibilities for \i wchar\i0 : a valid wide character code (one that can be translated to a multibyte character), an invalid code, and\f3  L'\\0'\f0 . 
\par 
\par Given a valid code, \f3 wctomb\f0  converts it to a multibyte character, storing the bytes starting at \i string\i0 . Then it returns the number of bytes in that character (always at least 1 and never more than \f3 MB_CUR_MAX\f0 ). 
\par 
\par If \i wchar\i0  is an invalid wide character code, \f3 wctomb\f0  returns -1. If \i wchar\i0  is \f3 L'\\0'\f0 , it returns \f3 0\f0 , also storing \f3 '\\0'\f0  in \f3 *\i\f0 string\i0 . 
\par 
\par If the multibyte character code uses shift characters, then\f3  wctomb\f0  maintains and updates a shift state as it scans. If you call \f3 wctomb\f0  with a null pointer for \i string\i0 , that initializes the shift state to its standard initial value. It also returns nonzero if the multibyte character code in use actually has a shift state. See  Shift State . 
\par 
\par Calling this function with a \i wchar\i0  argument of zero when\i  string\i0  is not null has the side-effect of reinitializing the stored shift state \i as well as\i0  storing the multibyte character\f3  '\\0'\f0  and returning 0.
\par 
\par \pard Similar to \f3 mbrlen\f0  there is also a non-reentrant function that computes the length of a multibyte character. It can be defined in terms of \f3 mbtowc\f0 .
\par -- Function: int \b mblen\b0  (\i const char *string, size_t size\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 The \f3 mblen\f0  function with a non-null \i string\i0  argument returns the number of bytes that make up the multibyte character beginning at\i  string\i0 , never examining more than \i size\i0  bytes. (The idea is to supply for \i size\i0  the number of bytes of data you have in hand.) 
\par 
\par The return value of \f3 mblen\f0  distinguishes three possibilities: the first \i size\i0  bytes at \i string\i0  start with valid multibyte characters, they start with an invalid byte sequence or just part of a character, or \i string\i0  points to an empty string (a null character). 
\par 
\par For a valid multibyte character, \f3 mblen\f0  returns the number of bytes in that character (always at least \f3 1\f0  and never more than\i  size\i0 ). For an invalid byte sequence, \f3 mblen\f0  returns -1. For an empty string, it returns 0. 
\par 
\par If the multibyte character code uses shift characters, then \f3 mblen\f0  maintains and updates a shift state as it scans. If you call\f3  mblen\f0  with a null pointer for \i string\i0 , that initializes the shift state to its standard initial value. It also returns a nonzero value if the multibyte character code in use actually has a shift state. See  Shift State . 
\par 
\par The function \f3 mblen\f0  is declared in \f3 stdlib.h\f0 .
\par 
