\par \b Numeric Input Conversions\b0 
\par 
\par This section describes the \f3 scanf\f0  conversions for reading numeric values. 
\par 
\par The `\f3 %d\f0 ' conversion matches an optionally signed integer in decimal radix. The syntax that is recognized is the same as that for the\f3  strtol\f0  function (see  Parsing of Integers ) with the value\f3  10\f0  for the \i base\i0  argument. 
\par 
\par The `\f3 %i\f0 ' conversion matches an optionally signed integer in any of the formats that the C language defines for specifying an integer constant. The syntax that is recognized is the same as that for the\f3  strtol\f0  function (see  Parsing of Integers ) with the value\f3  0\f0  for the \i base\i0  argument. (You can print integers in this syntax with \f3 printf\f0  by using the `\f3 #\f0 ' flag character with the `\f3 %x\f0 ', `\f3 %o\f0 ', or `\f3 %d\f0 ' conversion. See  Integer Conversions .) 
\par 
\par For example, any of the strings `\f3 10\f0 ', `\f3 0xa\f0 ', or `\f3 012\f0 ' could be read in as integers under the `\f3 %i\f0 ' conversion. Each of these specifies a number with decimal value \f3 10\f0 . 
\par 
\par The `\f3 %o\f0 ', `\f3 %u\f0 ', and `\f3 %x\f0 ' conversions match unsigned integers in octal, decimal, and hexadecimal radices, respectively. The syntax that is recognized is the same as that for the \f3 strtoul\f0  function (see  Parsing of Integers ) with the appropriate value (\f3 8\f0 , \f3 10\f0 , or \f3 16\f0 ) for the \i base\i0  argument. 
\par 
\par The `\f3 %X\f0 ' conversion is identical to the `\f3 %x\f0 ' conversion. They both permit either uppercase or lowercase letters to be used as digits. 
\par 
\par The default type of the corresponding argument for the \f3 %d\f0  and\f3  %i\f0  conversions is \f3 int *\f0 , and \f3 unsigned int *\f0  for the other integer conversions. You can use the following type modifiers to specify other sizes of integer:
\par 
\par `\f3 hh\f0 '
\par \pard\li500 Specifies that the argument is a \f3 signed char *\f0  or \f3 unsigned char *\f0 . 
\par 
\par This modifier was introduced in ISO C99. 
\par \pard `\f3 h\f0 '
\par \pard\li500 Specifies that the argument is a \f3 short int *\f0  or \f3 unsigned short int *\f0 . 
\par \pard `\f3 j\f0 '
\par \pard\li500 Specifies that the argument is a \f3 intmax_t *\f0  or \f3 uintmax_t *\f0 . 
\par 
\par This modifier was introduced in ISO C99. 
\par \pard `\f3 l\f0 '
\par \pard\li500 Specifies that the argument is a \f3 long int *\f0  or \f3 unsigned long int *\f0 . Two `\f3 l\f0 ' characters is like the `\f3 L\f0 ' modifier, below. 
\par 
\par If used with `\f3 %c\f0 ' or `\f3 %s\f0 ' the corresponding parameter is considered as a pointer to a wide character or wide character string respectively. This use of `\f3 l\f0 ' was introduced in Amendment 1 to ISO C90. 
\par \pard `\f3 ll\f0 '
\par \pard\li500 Specifies that the argument is a \f3 long long int *\f0  or \f3 unsigned long long int *\f0 . 
\par \pard `\f3 t\f0 '
\par \pard\li500 Specifies that the argument is a \f3 ptrdiff_t *\f0 . 
\par 
\par This modifier was introduced in ISO C99. 
\par \pard `\f3 z\f0 '
\par \pard\li500 Specifies that the argument is a \f3 size_t *\f0 . 
\par 
\par This modifier was introduced in ISO C99.
\par 
\par \pard All of the `\f3 %e\f0 ', `\f3 %f\f0 ', `\f3 %g\f0 ', `\f3 %E\f0 ', and `\f3 %G\f0 ' input conversions are interchangeable. They all match an optionally signed floating point number, in the same syntax as for the\f3  strtod\f0  function (see  Parsing of Floats ). 
\par 
\par For the floating-point input conversions, the default argument type is\f3  float *\f0 . (This is different from the corresponding output conversions, where the default type is \f3 double\f0 ; remember that\f3  float\f0  arguments to \f3 printf\f0  are converted to \f3 double\f0  by the default argument promotions, but \f3 float *\f0  arguments are not promoted to \f3 double *\f0 .) You can specify other sizes of float using these type modifiers:
\par 
\par `\f3 l\f0 '
\par \pard\li500 Specifies that the argument is of type \f3 double *\f0 . 
\par \pard `\f3 L\f0 '
\par \pard\li500 Specifies that the argument is of type \f3 long double *\f0 .
\par 
\par \pard For all the above number parsing formats there is an additional optional flag `\f3 '\f0 '. When this flag is given the \f3 scanf\f0  function expects the number represented in the input string to be formatted according to the grouping rules of the currently selected locale (see  General Numeric ). 
\par 
\par If the \f3 "C"\f0  or \f3 "POSIX"\f0  locale is selected there is no difference. But for a locale which specifies values for the appropriate fields in the locale the input must have the correct form in the input. Otherwise the longest prefix with a correct form is processed.
\par 
