\par \b Opening and Closing Files\b0 
\par 
\par This section describes the primitives for opening and closing files using file descriptors. The \f3 open\f0  and \f3 creat\f0  functions are declared in the header file \f3 fcntl.h\f0 , while \f3 close\f0  is declared in \f3 unistd.h\f0 .\f1 
\par \f0 
\par -- Function: int \b open\b0  (\i const char *filename, int flags\i0 [\i , mode_t mode\i0 ])
\par 
\par \pard\li500 The \f3 open\f0  function creates and returns a new file descriptor for the file named by \i filename\i0 . Initially, the file position indicator for the file is at the beginning of the file. The argument\i  mode\i0  is used only when a file is created, but it doesn't hurt to supply the argument in any case. 
\par 
\par The \i flags\i0  argument controls how the file is to be opened. This is a bit mask; you create the value by the bitwise OR of the appropriate parameters (using the `\f3 |\f0 ' operator in C). See  File Status Flags , for the parameters available. 
\par 
\par The normal return value from \f3 open\f0  is a non-negative integer file descriptor. In the case of an error, a value of -1 is returned instead. In addition to the usual file name errors (see  File Name Errors ), the following \f3 errno\f0  error conditions are defined for this function:
\par 
\par \f3 EACCES\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 The file exists but is not readable/writable as requested by the \i flags\i0  argument, the file does not exist and the directory is unwritable so it cannot be created. 
\par \pard\li500\f3 EEXIST\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 Both \f3 O_CREAT\f0  and \f3 O_EXCL\f0  are set, and the named file already exists. 
\par \pard\li500\f3 EMFILE\f0 
\par \f1            \f0 The process has too many files open. 
\par \f3 ENFILE\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 The entire system, or perhaps the file system which contains the directory, cannot support any additional open files at the moment. (This problem cannot happen on the GNU system.) 
\par \pard\li500\f3 ENOENT\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 The named file does not exist, and \f3 O_CREAT\f0  is not specified. 
\par \pard\li500\f3 ENOSPC\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 The directory or file system that would contain the new file cannot be extended, because there is no disk space left. 
\par \pard\li500\f3 ENXIO\f0 
\par \pard\li1000\f3 O_NONBLOCK\f0  and \f3 O_WRONLY\f0  are both set in the \i flags\i0  argument, the file named by \i filename\i0  is a FIFO (see  Pipes and FIFOs ), and no process has the file open for reading. 
\par \pard\li500\f3 EROFS\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 The file resides on a read-only file system and any of \f3 O_WRONLY\f0 ,\f3  O_RDWR\f0 , and \f3 O_TRUNC\f0  are set in the \i flags\i0  argument, or \f3 O_CREAT\f0  is set and the file does not already exist.
\par \pard\li500 
\par \pard -- Obsolete function: int \b creat\b0  (\i const char *filename, mode_t mode\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 This function is obsolete. The call: 
\par 
\par \f3           creat (\i filename\i0 , \i mode\i0 )
\par      
\par \f0 is equivalent to: 
\par 
\par \f3           open (\i filename\i0 , O_WRONLY | O_CREAT | O_TRUNC, \i mode\i0 )
\par      \f0 
\par \pard -- Function: int \b close\b0  (\i int filedes\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 The function \f3 close\f0  closes the file descriptor \i filedes\i0 . Closing a file has the following consequences:
\par 
\par \pard\li1000\f2\'b7\f0  The file descriptor is deallocated. 
\par \f2\'b7\f0  Any record locks owned by the process on the file are unlocked. 
\par \f2\'b7\f0  When all file descriptors associated with a pipe or FIFO have been closed, any unread data is discarded.
\par 
\par \pard\li500 This function is a cancellation point in multi-threaded programs. This is a problem if the thread allocates some resources (like memory, file descriptors, semaphores or whatever) at the time \f3 close\f0  is called. If the thread gets canceled these resources stay allocated until the program ends. To avoid this, calls to \f3 close\f0  should be protected using cancellation handlers. 
\par 
\par The normal return value from \f3 close\f0  is 0; a value of -1 is returned in case of failure. The following \f3 errno\f0  error conditions are defined for this function:
\par 
\par \f3 EBADF\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 The \i filedes\i0  argument is not a valid file descriptor. 
\par \pard\li500\f3 ENOSPC\f0 
\par \f3 EIO\f0 
\par \f3 EDQUOT\f0 
\par \pard\li1000 When the file is accessed by NFS, these errors from \f3 write\f0  can sometimes not be detected until \f3 close\f0 . See  I/O Primitives , for details on their meaning.
\par 
\par \pard To close a stream, call \f3 fclose\f0  (see  Closing Streams ) instead of trying to close its underlying file descriptor with \f3 close\f0 . This flushes any buffered output and updates the stream object to indicate that it is closed.
\par 
\par \pard\plain\f0

