\par \b Other Input Conversions\b0 
\par 
\par This section describes the miscellaneous input conversions. 
\par 
\par The `\f3 %p\f0 ' conversion is used to read a pointer value. It recognizes the same syntax used by the `\f3 %p\f0 ' output conversion for\f3  printf\f0  (see  Other Output Conversions ); that is, a hexadecimal number just as the `\f3 %x\f0 ' conversion accepts. The corresponding argument should be of type \f3 void **\f0 ; that is, the address of a place to store a pointer. 
\par 
\par The resulting pointer value is not guaranteed to be valid if it was not originally written during the same program execution that reads it in. 
\par 
\par The `\f3 %n\f0 ' conversion produces the number of characters read so far by this call. The corresponding argument should be of type \f3 int *\f0 . This conversion works in the same way as the `\f3 %n\f0 ' conversion for\f3  printf\f0 ; see  Other Output Conversions , for an example. 
\par 
\par The `\f3 %n\f0 ' conversion is the only mechanism for determining the success of literal matches or conversions with suppressed assignments. If the `\f3 %n\f0 ' follows the locus of a matching failure, then no value is stored for it since \f3 scanf\f0  returns before processing the `\f3 %n\f0 '. If you store \f3 -1\f0  in that argument slot before calling\f3  scanf\f0 , the presence of \f3 -1\f0  after \f3 scanf\f0  indicates an error occurred before the `\f3 %n\f0 ' was reached. 
\par 
\par Finally, the `\f3 %%\f0 ' conversion matches a literal `\f3 %\f0 ' character in the input stream, without using an argument. This conversion does not permit any flags, field width, or type modifier to be specified.
\par 
\par \pard\plain\f0

