\par \b Other Output Conversions\b0 
\par 
\par This section describes miscellaneous conversions for \f3 printf\f0 . 
\par 
\par The `\f3 %c\f0 ' conversion prints a single character. In case there is no `\f3 l\f0 ' modifier the \f3 int\f0  argument is first converted to an\f3  unsigned char\f0 . Then, if used in a wide stream function, the character is converted into the corresponding wide character. The `\f3 -\f0 ' flag can be used to specify left-justification in the field, but no other flags are defined, and no precision or type modifier can be given. For example:
\par 
\par \f3      printf ("%c%c%c%c%c", 'h', 'e', 'l', 'l', 'o');
\par \f0 
\par prints `\f3 hello\f0 '. 
\par 
\par If there is a `\f3 l\f0 ' modifier present the argument is expected to be of type \f3 wint_t\f0 . If used in a multibyte function the wide character is converted into a multibyte character before being added to the output. In this case more than one output byte can be produced. 
\par 
\par The `\f3 %s\f0 ' conversion prints a string. If no `\f3 l\f0 ' modifier is present the corresponding argument must be of type \f3 char *\f0  (or\f3  const char *\f0 ). If used in a wide stream function the string is first converted in a wide character string. A precision can be specified to indicate the maximum number of characters to write; otherwise characters in the string up to but not including the terminating null character are written to the output stream. The `\f3 -\f0 ' flag can be used to specify left-justification in the field, but no other flags or type modifiers are defined for this conversion. For example:
\par 
\par \f3      printf ("%3s%-6s", "no", "where");
\par \f0 
\par prints `\f3  nowhere \f0 '. 
\par 
\par If there is a `\f3 l\f0 ' modifier present the argument is expected to be of type \f3 wchar_t\f0  (or \f3 const wchar_t *\f0 ). 
\par 
\par If you accidentally pass a null pointer as the argument for a `\f3 %s\f0 ' conversion, the GNU library prints it as `\f3 (null)\f0 '. We think this is more useful than crashing. But it's not good practice to pass a null argument intentionally. 
\par 
\par The `\f3 %p\f0 ' conversion prints a pointer value. The corresponding argument must be of type \f3 void *\f0 . In practice, you can use any type of pointer. 
\par 
\par In th\f1 is system, \f0 pointers are printed as unsigned integers, as if a `\f3 %#x\f0 ' conversion were used.
\par 
\par For example:
\par 
\par \f3      printf ("%p", "testing");
\par \f0 
\par prints `\f3 0x\f0 ' followed by a hexadecimal number--the address of the string constant \f3 "testing"\f0 . It does not print the word `\f3 testing\f0 '. 
\par 
\par You can supply the `\f3 -\f0 ' flag with the `\f3 %p\f0 ' conversion to specify left-justification, but no other flags, precision, or type modifiers are defined. 
\par 
\par The `\f3 %n\f0 ' conversion is unlike any of the other output conversions. It uses an argument which must be a pointer to an \f3 int\f0 , but instead of printing anything it stores the number of characters printed so far by this call at that location. The `\f3 h\f0 ' and `\f3 l\f0 ' type modifiers are permitted to specify that the argument is of type\f3  short int *\f0  or \f3 long int *\f0  instead of \f3 int *\f0 , but no flags, field width, or precision are permitted. 
\par 
\par For example,
\par 
\par \f3      int nchar;
\par      printf ("%d %s%n\\n", 3, "bears", &nchar);
\par \f0 
\par prints:
\par 
\par \f3      3 bears
\par \f0 
\par and sets \f3 nchar\f0  to \f3 7\f0 , because `\f3 3 bears\f0 ' is seven characters. 
\par 
\par The `\f3 %%\f0 ' conversion prints a literal `\f3 %\f0 ' character. This conversion doesn't use an argument, and no flags, field width, precision, or type modifiers are permitted.
\par 
\par \pard\plain\f0

