\par \b Parsing of Floats\b0 
\par 
\par The `\f3 str\f0 ' functions are declared in \f3 stdlib.h\f0  and those beginning with `\f3 wcs\f0 ' are declared in \f3 wchar.h\f0 . One might wonder about the use of \f3 restrict\f0  in the prototypes of the functions in this section. It is seemingly useless but the ISO C standard uses it (for the functions defined there) so we have to do it as well.
\par 
\par -- Function: double \b strtod\b0  (\i const char *restrict string, char **restrict tailptr\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 The \f3 strtod\f0  ("string-to-double") function converts the initial part of \i string\i0  to a floating-point number, which is returned as a value of type \f3 double\f0 . 
\par 
\par This function attempts to decompose \i string\i0  as follows:
\par 
\par \pard\li1000\f2\'b7\f0  A (possibly empty) sequence of whitespace characters. Which characters are whitespace is determined by the \f3 isspace\f0  function (see  Classification of Characters ). These are discarded. 
\par \f2\'b7\f0  An optional plus or minus sign (`\f3 +\f0 ' or `\f3 -\f0 '). 
\par \f2\'b7\f0  A floating point number in decimal or hexadecimal format. The decimal format is:
\par 
\par \pard\li1500\f2\'b7\f0  A nonempty sequence of digits optionally containing a decimal-point character--normally `\f3 .\f0 ', but it depends on the locale (see  General Numeric ). 
\par \f2\'b7\f0  An optional exponent part, consisting of a character `\f3 e\f0 ' or `\f3 E\f0 ', an optional sign, and a sequence of digits.
\par 
\par \pard\li1000 The hexadecimal format is as follows:
\par 
\par \pard\li1500\f2\'b7\f0  A 0x or 0X followed by a nonempty sequence of hexadecimal digits optionally containing a decimal-point character--normally `\f3 .\f0 ', but it depends on the locale (see  General Numeric ). 
\par \f2\'b7\f0  An optional binary-exponent part, consisting of a character `\f3 p\f0 ' or `\f3 P\f0 ', an optional sign, and a sequence of digits.
\par 
\par \pard\li1000\f2\'b7\f0  Any remaining characters in the string. If \i tailptr\i0  is not a null pointer, a pointer to this tail of the string is stored in\f3  *\i\f0 tailptr\i0 .
\par 
\par \pard\li500 If the string is empty, contains only whitespace, or does not contain an initial substring that has the expected syntax for a floating-point number, no conversion is performed. In this case, \f3 strtod\f0  returns a value of zero and the value returned in \f3 *\i\f0 tailptr\i0  is the value of \i string\i0 . 
\par 
\par In a locale other than the standard \f3 "C"\f0  or \f3 "POSIX"\f0  locales, this function may recognize additional locale-dependent syntax. 
\par 
\par If the string has valid syntax for a floating-point number but the value is outside the range of a \f3 double\f0 , \f3 strtod\f0  will signal overflow or underflow as described in  Math Error Reporting . 
\par 
\par \f3 strtod\f0  recognizes four special input strings. The strings\f3  "inf"\f0  and \f3 "infinity"\f0  are converted to &infin;, or to the largest representable value if the floating-point format doesn't support infinities. You can prepend a \f3 "+"\f0  or \f3 "-"\f0  to specify the sign. Case is ignored when scanning these strings. 
\par 
\par The strings \f3 "nan"\f0  and \f3 "nan(\i\f0 chars...\i0\f3 )"\f0  are converted to NaN. Again, case is ignored. If \i chars...\i0  are provided, they are used in some unspecified fashion to select a particular representation of NaN (there can be several). 
\par 
\par Since zero is a valid result as well as the value returned on error, you should check for errors in the same way as for \f3 strtol\f0 , by examining \i errno\i0  and \i tailptr\i0 .
\par 
\par \pard -- Function: float \b strtof\b0  (\i const char *string, char **tailptr\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 -- Function: long double \b strtold\b0  (\i const char *string, char **tailptr\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li1000 These functions are analogous to \f3 strtod\f0 , but return \f3 float\f0  and \f3 long double\f0  values respectively. They report errors in the same way as \f3 strtod\f0 . \f3 strtof\f0  can be substantially faster than \f3 strtod\f0 , but has less precision; conversely, \f3 strtold\f0  can be much slower but has more precision (on systems where \f3 long double\f0  is a separate type). 
\par 
\par These functions have been GNU extensions and are new to ISO C99.
\par 
\par \pard -- Function: double \b wcstod\b0  (\i const wchar_t *restrict string, wchar_t **restrict tailptr\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 -- Function: float \b wcstof\b0  (\i const wchar_t *string, wchar_t **tailptr\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li1000 -- Function: long double \b wcstold\b0  (\i const wchar_t *string, wchar_t **tailptr\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li1500 The \f3 wcstod\f0 , \f3 wcstof\f0 , and \f3 wcstol\f0  functions are equivalent in nearly all aspect to the \f3 strtod\f0 , \f3 strtof\f0 , and\f3  strtold\f0  functions but it handles wide character string. 
\par 
\par The \f3 wcstod\f0  function was introduced in Amendment 1 of ISO C90. The \f3 wcstof\f0  and \f3 wcstold\f0  functions were introduced in ISO C99.
\par 
\par \pard -- Function: double \b atof\b0  (\i const char *string\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 This function is similar to the \f3 strtod\f0  function, except that it need not detect overflow and underflow errors. The \f3 atof\f0  function is provided mostly for compatibility with existing code; using\f3  strtod\f0  is more robust.
