\par -- Function: long int \b strtol\b0  (\i const char *restrict string, char **restrict tailptr, int base\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 The \f3 strtol\f0  ("string-to-long") function converts the initial part of \i string\i0  to a signed integer, which is returned as a value of type \f3 long int\f0 . 
\par 
\par This function attempts to decompose \i string\i0  as follows:
\par 
\par \pard\li1000\f2\'b7\f0  A (possibly empty) sequence of whitespace characters. Which characters are whitespace is determined by the \f3 isspace\f0  function (see  Classification of Characters ). These are discarded. 
\par \f2\'b7\f0  An optional plus or minus sign (`\f3 +\f0 ' or `\f3 -\f0 '). 
\par \f2\'b7\f0  A nonempty sequence of digits in the radix specified by \i base\i0 . 
\par 
\par If \i base\i0  is zero, decimal radix is assumed unless the series of digits begins with `\f3 0\f0 ' (specifying octal radix), or `\f3 0x\f0 ' or `\f3 0X\f0 ' (specifying hexadecimal radix); in other words, the same syntax used for integer constants in C. 
\par 
\par Otherwise \i base\i0  must have a value between \f3 2\f0  and \f3 36\f0 . If \i base\i0  is \f3 16\f0 , the digits may optionally be preceded by `\f3 0x\f0 ' or `\f3 0X\f0 '. If base has no legal value the value returned is \f3 0l\f0  and the global variable \f3 errno\f0  is set to \f3 EINVAL\f0 . 
\par \f2\'b7\f0  Any remaining characters in the string. If \i tailptr\i0  is not a null pointer, \f3 strtol\f0  stores a pointer to this tail in\f3  *\i\f0 tailptr\i0 .
\par 
\par \pard\li500 If the string is empty, contains only whitespace, or does not contain an initial substring that has the expected syntax for an integer in the specified \i base\i0 , no conversion is performed. In this case,\f3  strtol\f0  returns a value of zero and the value stored in\f3  *\i\f0 tailptr\i0  is the value of \i string\i0 . 
\par 
\par In a locale other than the standard \f3 "C"\f0  locale, this function may recognize additional implementation-dependent syntax. 
\par 
\par If the string has valid syntax for an integer but the value is not representable because of overflow, \f3 strtol\f0  returns either\f3  LONG_MAX\f0  or \f3 LONG_MIN\f0  (see  Range of Type ), as appropriate for the sign of the value. It also sets \f3 errno\f0  to \f3 ERANGE\f0  to indicate there was overflow. 
\par 
\par You should not check for errors by examining the return value of\f3  strtol\f0 , because the string might be a valid representation of\f3  0l\f0 , \f3 LONG_MAX\f0 , or \f3 LONG_MIN\f0 . Instead, check whether\i  tailptr\i0  points to what you expect after the number (e.g. \f3 '\\0'\f0  if the string should end after the number). You also need to clear \i errno\i0  before the call and check it afterward, in case there was overflow. 
\par 
\par There is an example at the end of this section.
\par 
\par \pard -- Function: long int \b wcstol\b0  (\i const wchar_t *restrict string, wchar_t **restrict tailptr, int base\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 The \f3 wcstol\f0  function is equivalent to the \f3 strtol\f0  function in nearly all aspects but handles wide character strings. 
\par 
\par The \f3 wcstol\f0  function was introduced in Amendment 1 of ISO C90.
\par 
\par \pard -- Function: unsigned long int \b strtoul\b0  (\i const char *retrict string, char **restrict tailptr, int base\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 The \f3 strtoul\f0  ("string-to-unsigned-long") function is like\f3  strtol\f0  except it converts to an \f3 unsigned long int\f0  value. The syntax is the same as described above for \f3 strtol\f0 . The value returned on overflow is \f3 ULONG_MAX\f0  (see  Range of Type ). 
\par 
\par If \i string\i0  depicts a negative number, \f3 strtoul\f0  acts the same as \i strtol\i0  but casts the result to an unsigned integer. That means for example that \f3 strtoul\f0  on \f3 "-1"\f0  returns \f3 ULONG_MAX\f0  and an input more negative than \f3 LONG_MIN\f0  returns (\f3 ULONG_MAX\f0  + 1) / 2. 
\par 
\par \f3 strtoul\f0  sets \i errno\i0  to \f3 EINVAL\f0  if \i base\i0  is out of range, or \f3 ERANGE\f0  on overflow.
\par 
\par \pard -- Function: unsigned long int \b wcstoul\b0  (\i const wchar_t *restrict string, wchar_t **restrict tailptr, int base\i0 )
\par 
