\par \b Portable File-Position Functions\b0 
\par \f1 
\par In this\f0  system, the file position is truly a character count. You can specify any character count value as an argument to \f3 fseek\f0  and get reliable results for any random access file. However, \f1 other ISO C systems may not represent file positions in this manner.\f0 
\par 
\par As a consequence, you must observe certain rules\f1  when writing code which is portable to these systems\f0 :
\par 
\par \pard\li500\f2\'b7\f0  The value returned from \f3 ftell\f0  on a text stream has no predictable relationship to the number of characters you have read so far. The only thing you can rely on is that you can use it subsequently as the\i  offset\i0  argument to \f3 fseek\f0  or \f3 fseeko\f0  to move back to the same file position. 
\par \f2\'b7\f0  In a call to \f3 fseek\f0  on a text stream, either the\i  offset\i0  must be zero, or \i whence\i0  must be \f3 SEEK_SET\f0  and and the \i offset\i0  must be the result of an earlier call to \f3 ftell\f0  on the same stream. 
\par \f2\'b7\f0  The value of the file position indicator of a text stream is undefined while there are characters that have been pushed back with \f3 ungetc\f0  that haven't been read or discarded. See  Unreading .
\par 
\par \pard\f1 I\f0 f you do want to support systems with peculiar encodings for the file positions, it is better to use the functions \f3 fgetpos\f0  and\f3  fsetpos\f0  instead. These functions represent the file position using the data type \f3 fpos_t\f0 , whose internal representation varies from system to system. 
\par 
\par These symbols are declared in the header file \f3 stdio.h\f0 .
\par 
\par -- Data Type: \b fpos_t\b0 
\par 
\par \pard\li500 This is the type of an object that can encode information about the file position of a stream, for use by the functions \f3 fgetpos\f0  and\f3  fsetpos\f0 . 
\par 
\par In the GNU system, \f3 fpos_t\f0  is an opaque data structure that contains internal data to represent file offset and conversion state information. In other systems, it might have a different internal representation. 
\par 
\par \pard -- Function: int \b fgetpos\b0  (\i FILE *stream, fpos_t *position\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 This function stores the value of the file position indicator for the stream \i stream\i0  in the \f3 fpos_t\f0  object pointed to by\i  position\i0 . If successful, \f3 fgetpos\f0  returns zero; otherwise it returns a nonzero value and stores an implementation-defined positive value in \f3 errno\f0 . 
\par 
\par \pard -- Function: int \b fsetpos\b0  (\i FILE *stream, const fpos_t *position\i0 )
\par 
