\par \fs18 
\par \b Program Arguments\b0 
\par 
\par The system starts a C program by calling the function \f3 main\f0 . It is up to you to write a function named \f3 main\f0 --otherwise, you won't even be able to link your program without errors. 
\par 
\par In ISO C you can define \f3 main\f0  either to take no arguments, or to take two arguments that represent the command line arguments to the program, like this:
\par 
\par \f3      int main (int \i argc\i0 , char *\i argv\i0 [])
\par \f0 
\par The command line arguments are the whitespace-separated tokens given in the shell command used to invoke the program; thus, in `\f3 cat foo bar\f0 ', the arguments are `\f3 foo\f0 ' and `\f3 bar\f0 '. \f1  A program may also look at its arguments by examining the \i __argv\i0  and \i __argc\i0  variables\f0 
\par 
\par 
\par The value of the \i argc\i0  argument is the number of command line arguments. The \i argv\i0  argument is a vector of C strings; its elements are the individual command line argument strings. The file name of the program being run is also included in the vector as the first element; the value of \i argc\i0  counts this element. A null pointer always follows the last element: \i argv\i0\f3 [\i\f0 argc\i0\f3 ]\f0  is this null pointer. 
\par 
\par For the command `\f3 cat foo bar\f0 ', \i argc\i0  is 3 and \i argv\i0  has three elements, \f3 "cat"\f0 , \f3 "foo"\f0  and \f3 "bar"\f0 . 
\par 
\par In \f1 this \f0 systems you can define \f3 main\f0  a third way, using three arguments:
\par 
\par \f3      int main (int \i argc\i0 , char *\i argv\i0 [], char *\i envp\i0 [])
\par \f0 
\par The first two arguments are just the same. The third argument\i  envp\i0  gives the program's environment; it is the same as the value of \f1 _\f3 environ\f0 . See  Environment Variables . POSIX.1 does not allow this three-argument form, so to be portable it is best to write\f3  main\f0  to take two arguments, and use the value of \f1 _\f3 environ\f0 .
\par \f2 
\par \pard\plain\f0

