\par \b Program Termination\b0 
\par 
\par The usual way for a program to terminate is simply for its \f3 main\f0  function to return. The \i exit status value\i0  returned from the\f3  main\f0  function is used to report information back to the process's parent process or shell. 
\par 
\par A program can also terminate normally by calling the \f3 exit\f0  function. 
\par 
\par In addition, programs can be terminated by signals; this is discussed in more detail in  Signal Handling . The \f3 abort\f0  function causes a signal that kills the program.
\par 
\par \pard\li500\f2\'b7\f0   Normal Termination : If a program calls \f3 exit\f0 , a process terminates normally.
\par \f2\'b7\f0   Exit Status : The \f3 exit status\f0  provides information about why the process terminated.
\par \f2\'b7\f0   Cleanups on Exit : A process can run its own cleanup functions upon normal termination.
\par \f2\'b7\f0   Aborting a Program : The \f3 abort\f0  function causes abnormal program termination.
\par \f2 
