\par \b Range of an Integer Type\b0 
\par 
\par Suppose you need to store an integer value which can range from zero to one million. Which is the smallest type you can use? There is no general rule; it depends on the C compiler and target machine. You can use the `\f3 MIN\f0 ' and `\f3 MAX\f0 ' macros in \f3 limits.h\f0  to determine which type will work. 
\par 
\par Each signed integer type has a pair of macros which give the smallest and largest values that it can hold. Each unsigned integer type has one such macro, for the maximum value; the minimum value is, of course, zero. 
\par 
\par The values of these macros are all integer constant expressions. The `\f3 MAX\f0 ' and `\f3 MIN\f0 ' macros for \f3 char\f0  and \f3 short int\f0  types have values of type \f3 int\f0 . The `\f3 MAX\f0 ' and `\f3 MIN\f0 ' macros for the other types have values of the same type described by the macro--thus, \f3 ULONG_MAX\f0  has type\f3  unsigned long int\f0 .
\par 
\par \f3 SCHAR_MIN\f0 
\par \pard\li500 This is the minimum value that can be represented by a \f3 signed char\f0 .
\par \pard\f3 SCHAR_MAX\f0 
\par \f3 UCHAR_MAX\f0 
\par \pard\li500 These are the maximum values that can be represented by a\f3  signed char\f0  and \f3 unsigned char\f0 , respectively.
\par \pard\f3 CHAR_MIN\f0 
\par \pard\li500 This is the minimum value that can be represented by a \f3 char\f0 . It's equal to \f3 SCHAR_MIN\f0  if \f3 char\f0  is signed, or zero otherwise.
\par \pard\f3 CHAR_MAX\f0 
\par \pard\li500 This is the maximum value that can be represented by a \f3 char\f0 . It's equal to \f3 SCHAR_MAX\f0  if \f3 char\f0  is signed, or\f3  UCHAR_MAX\f0  otherwise.
\par \pard\f3 SHRT_MIN\f0 
\par \pard\li500 This is the minimum value that can be represented by a \f3 signed short int\f0 . \f1  In this system\f0 ,\f3  short\f0  integers are 16-bit quantities.
\par \pard\f3 SHRT_MAX\f0 
\par \f3 USHRT_MAX\f0 
\par \pard\li500 These are the maximum values that can be represented by a\f3  signed short int\f0  and \f3 unsigned short int\f0 , respectively.
\par \pard\f3 INT_MIN\f0 
\par \pard\li500 This is the minimum value that can be represented by a \f3 signed int\f0 .\f1   In this system\f0 , an \f3 int\f0  is a 32-bit quantity.
\par \pard\f3 INT_MAX\f0 
\par \f3 UINT_MAX\f0 
\par \pard\li500 These are the maximum values that can be represented by, respectively, the type \f3 signed int\f0  and the type \f3 unsigned int\f0 .
\par \pard\f3 LONG_MIN\f0 
\par \pard\li500 This is the minimum value that can be represented by a \f3 signed long int\f0 . \f1 I\f0 n \f1 this system, \f3 long\f0  integers are 32-bit quantities, the same size as \f3 int\f0 .
\par \pard\f3 LONG_MAX\f0 
\par \f3 ULONG_MAX\f0 
\par \pard\li500 These are the maximum values that can be represented by a\f3  signed long int\f0  and \f3 unsigned long int\f0 , respectively.
\par \pard\f3 LONG_LONG_MIN\f0 
\par \pard\li500 This is the minimum value that can be represented by a \f3 signed long long int\f0 . \f1 In this system\f0 ,\f3  long long\f0  integers are 64-bit quantities.
\par \pard\f3 LONG_LONG_MAX\f0 
\par \f3 ULONG_LONG_MAX\f0 
\par \pard\li500 These are the maximum values that can be represented by a \f3 signed long long int\f0  and \f3 unsigned long long int\f0 , respectively.
\par \pard\f3 WCHAR_MAX\f0 
\par \pard\li500 This is the maximum value that can be represented by a \f3 wchar_t\f0 . See  Extended Char Intro .
\par \pard 
