\viewkind4\uc1\pard\qc\lang1033\f0\fs24 Setting the Locale 
\par \pard\fs18 Next:  Standard Locales , Previous:  Locale Categories , Up:  Locales 
\par \fs10 
\par \pard\ri100\fs2 
\par \pard\fs10 
\par \fs18 
\par \b How Programs Set the Locale\b0 
\par 
\par A C program inherits its locale environment variables when it starts up. This happens automatically. However, these variables do not automatically control the locale used by the library functions, because ISO C says that all programs start by default in the standard `\f3 C\f0 ' locale. To use the locales specified by the environment, you must call\f3  setlocale\f0 . Call it as follows:
\par 
\par \f3      setlocale (LC_ALL, "");
\par \f0 
\par to select a locale based on the user choice of the appropriate environment variables. 
\par 
\par You can also use \f3 setlocale\f0  to specify a particular locale, for general use or for a specific category. 
\par 
\par The symbols in this section are defined in the header file \f3 locale.h\f0 .
\par -- Function: char * \b setlocale\b0  (\i int category, const char *locale\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 The function \f3 setlocale\f0  sets the current locale for category\i  category\i0  to \i locale\i0 . A list of all the locales the system provides can be created by running
\par 
\par \f3             locale -a
\par      
\par \f0 If \i category\i0  is \f3 LC_ALL\f0 , this specifies the locale for all purposes. The other possible values of \i category\i0  specify an single purpose (see  Locale Categories ). 
\par 
\par You can also use this function to find out the current locale by passing a null pointer as the \i locale\i0  argument. In this case,\f3  setlocale\f0  returns a string that is the name of the locale currently selected for category \i category\i0 . 
\par 
\par The string returned by \f3 setlocale\f0  can be overwritten by subsequent calls, so you should make a copy of the string (see  Copying and Concatenation ) if you want to save it past any further calls to\f3  setlocale\f0 . (The standard library is guaranteed never to call\f3  setlocale\f0  itself.) 
\par 
\par You should not modify the string returned by \f3 setlocale\f0 . It might be the same string that was passed as an argument in a previous call to\f3  setlocale\f0 . One requirement is that the \i category\i0  must be the same in the call the string was returned and the one when the string is passed in as \i locale\i0  parameter. 
\par 
\par When you read the current locale for category \f3 LC_ALL\f0 , the value encodes the entire combination of selected locales for all categories. In this case, the value is not just a single locale name. In fact, we don't make any promises about what it looks like. But if you specify the same "locale name" with \f3 LC_ALL\f0  in a subsequent call to\f3  setlocale\f0 , it restores the same combination of locale selections. 
\par 
\par To be sure you can use the returned string encoding the currently selected locale at a later time, you must make a copy of the string. It is not guaranteed that the returned pointer remains valid over time. 
\par 
\par When the \i locale\i0  argument is not a null pointer, the string returned by \f3 setlocale\f0  reflects the newly-modified locale. 
\par 
\par If you specify an empty string for \i locale\i0 , this means to read the appropriate environment variable and use its value to select the locale for \i category\i0 . 
\par 
\par If a nonempty string is given for \i locale\i0 , then the locale of that name is used if possible. 
\par 
\par If you specify an invalid locale name, \f3 setlocale\f0  returns a null pointer and leaves the current locale unchanged.
\par 
\par \pard Here is an example showing how you might use \f3 setlocale\f0  to temporarily switch to a new locale.
\par 
\par \f3      #include <stddef.h>
\par      #include <locale.h>
\par      #include <stdlib.h>
\par      #include <string.h>
\par      
\par      void
\par      with_other_locale (char *new_locale,
\par                         void (*subroutine) (int),
\par                         int argument)
\par      \{
\par        char *old_locale, *saved_locale;
\par      
\par        /* Get the name of the current locale.  */
\par        old_locale = setlocale (LC_ALL, NULL);
\par      
\par        /* Copy the name so it won't be clobbered by setlocale. */
\par        saved_locale = strdup (old_locale);
\par        if (saved_locale == NULL)
\par          fatal ("Out of memory");
\par      
\par        /* Now change the locale and do some stuff with it. */
\par        setlocale (LC_ALL, new_locale);
\par        (*subroutine) (argument);
\par      
\par        /* Restore the original locale. */
\par        setlocale (LC_ALL, saved_locale);
\par        free (saved_locale);
\par      \}
\par \f0 
\par \b Portability Note:\b0  Some ISO C systems may define additional locale categories, and future versions of the library will do so. For portability, assume that any symbol beginning with `\f3 LC_\f0 ' might be defined in \f3 locale.h\f0 .
\par 
\par \pard\plain\f0

