\par \b Simple Calendar Time\b0 
\par 
\par This section describes the \f3 time_t\f0  data type for representing calendar time as simple time, and the functions which operate on simple time objects. These facilities are declared in the header file \f3 time.h\f0 .
\par -- Data Type: \b time_t\b0 
\par 
\par \pard\li500 This is the data type used to represent simple time. Sometimes, it also represents an elapsed time. When interpreted as a calendar time value, it represents the number of seconds elapsed since 00:00:00 on January 1, 1970, Coordinated Universal Time. (This calendar time is sometimes referred to as the \i epoch\i0 .) POSIX requires that this count not include leap seconds, but on some systems this count includes leap seconds if you set \f3 TZ\f0  to certain values (see  TZ Variable ). 
\par 
\par Note that a simple time has no concept of local time zone. Calendar Time \i T\i0  is the same instant in time regardless of where on the globe the computer is. 
\par 
\par In th\f1 is\f0  C library, \f3 time_t\f0  is equivalent to \f3 long\f2  \f3 int\f0 . In other systems, \f3 time_t\f0  might be either an integer or floating-point type.
\par 
\par \pard The function \f3 difftime\f0  tells you the elapsed time between two simple calendar times, which is not always as easy to compute as just subtracting. See  Elapsed Time .
\par 
\par -- Function: time_t \b time\b0  (\i time_t *result\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 The \f3 time\f0  function returns the current calendar time as a value of type \f3 time_t\f0 . If the argument \i result\i0  is not a null pointer, the calendar time value is also stored in \f3 *\i\f0 result\i0 . If the current calendar time is not available, the value\f3  (time_t)(-1)\f0  is returned.
\par 
\par \pard -- Function: int \b stime\b0  (\i time_t *newtime\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500\f3 stime\f0  sets the system clock, i.e. it tells the system that the current calendar time is \i newtime\i0 , where \f3 newtime\f0  is interpreted as described in the above definition of \f3 time_t\f0 . 
\par 
\par If the function succeeds, the return value is zero.
\par \pard\plain\f0

