\par \b Simple Output by Characters or Lines\b0 
\par 
\par This section describes functions for performing character- and line-oriented output. 
\par 
\par These narrow streams functions are declared in the header file\f3  stdio.h\f0  and the wide stream functions in \f3 wchar.h\f0 .
\par 
\par -- Function: int \b fputc\b0  (\i int c, FILE *stream\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 The \f3 fputc\f0  function converts the character \i c\i0  to type\f3  unsigned char\f0 , and writes it to the stream \i stream\i0 .\f3  EOF\f0  is returned if a write error occurs; otherwise the character \i c\i0  is returned.
\par 
\par \pard -- Function: wint_t \b fputwc\b0  (\i wchar_t wc, FILE *stream\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 The \f3 fputwc\f0  function writes the wide character \i wc\i0  to the stream \i stream\i0 . \f3 WEOF\f0  is returned if a write error occurs; otherwise the character \i wc\i0  is returned.
\par \pard 
\par -- Function: int \b putc\b0  (\i int c, FILE *stream\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 This is just like \f3 fputc\f0 , except that most systems implement it as a macro, making it faster. One consequence is that it may evaluate the\i  stream\i0  argument more than once, which is an exception to the general rule for macros. \f3 putc\f0  is usually the best function to use for writing a single character.
\par 
\par \pard -- Function: wint_t \b putwc\b0  (\i wchar_t wc, FILE *stream\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 This is just like \f3 fputwc\f0 , except that it can be implement as a macro, making it faster. One consequence is that it may evaluate the\i  stream\i0  argument more than once, which is an exception to the general rule for macros. \f3 putwc\f0  is usually the best function to use for writing a single wide character.
\par 
\par \pard -- Function: int \b putchar\b0  (\i int c\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 The \f3 putchar\f0  function is equivalent to \f3 putc\f0  with\f3  stdout\f0  as the value of the \i stream\i0  argument.
\par 
\par \pard -- Function: wint_t \b putwchar\b0  (\i wchar_t wc\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 The \f3 putwchar\f0  function is equivalent to \f3 putwc\f0  with\f3  stdout\f0  as the value of the \i stream\i0  argument.
\par 
\par \pard -- Function: int \b fputs\b0  (\i const char *s, FILE *stream\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 The function \f3 fputs\f0  writes the string \i s\i0  to the stream\i  stream\i0 . The terminating null character is not written. This function does \i not\i0  add a newline character, either. It outputs only the characters in the string. 
\par 
\par This function returns \f3 EOF\f0  if a write error occurs, and otherwise a non-negative value. 
\par 
\par For example: 
\par 
\par \f3           fputs ("Are ", stdout);
\par           fputs ("you ", stdout);
\par           fputs ("hungry?\\n", stdout);
\par      
\par \f0 outputs the text `\f3 Are you hungry?\f0 ' followed by a newline.
\par 
\par \pard -- Function: int \b fputws\b0  (\i const wchar_t *ws, FILE *stream\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 The function \f3 fputws\f0  writes the wide character string \i ws\i0  to the stream \i stream\i0 . The terminating null character is not written. This function does \i not\i0  add a newline character, either. It outputs only the characters in the string. 
\par 
\par This function returns \f3 WEOF\f0  if a write error occurs, and otherwise a non-negative value.
\par 
\par \pard -- Function: int \b puts\b0  (\i const char *s\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 The \f3 puts\f0  function writes the string \i s\i0  to the stream\f3  stdout\f0  followed by a newline. The terminating null character of the string is not written. (Note that \f3 fputs\f0  does \i not\i0  write a newline as this function does.) 
\par 
\par \f3 puts\f0  is the most convenient function for printing simple messages. For example: 
\par 
\par \f3           puts ("This is a message.");
\par      
\par \f0 outputs the text `\f3 This is a message.\f0 ' followed by a newline.
\par \pard\plain\f0

