\par \pard\fs10 
\par \fs18 
\par \b Sleeping\b0 
\par 
\par The function \f3 sleep\f0  gives a simple way to make the program wait for a short interval. If your program doesn't use signals (except to terminate), then you can expect \f3 sleep\f0  to wait reliably throughout the specified interval. Otherwise, \f3 sleep\f0  can return sooner if a signal arrives\f1 .
\par 
\par \f0 -- Function: unsigned int \b sleep\b0  (\i unsigned int seconds\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 The \f3 sleep\f0  function waits for \i seconds\i0  or until a signal is delivered, whichever happens first. 
\par 
\par If \f3 sleep\f0  function returns because the requested interval is over, it returns a value of zero. If it returns because of delivery of a signal, its return value is the remaining time in the sleep interval. 
\par 
\par The \f3 sleep\f0  function is declared in \f3 unistd.h\f0 .
\par 
\par \pard Resist the temptation to implement a sleep for a fixed amount of time by using the return value of \f3 sleep\f0 , when nonzero, to call\f3  sleep\f0  again. This will work with a certain amount of accuracy as long as signals arrive infrequently. But each signal can cause the eventual wakeup time to be off by an additional second or so. Suppose a few signals happen to arrive in rapid succession by bad luck--there is no limit on how much this could shorten or lengthen the wait. 
\par 
\par Instead, compute the calendar time at which the program should stop waiting, and keep trying to wait until that calendar time. This won't be off by more than a second. With just a little more work, you can use\f3  select\f0  and make the waiting period quite accurate. (Of course, heavy system load can cause additional unavoidable delays--unless the machine is dedicated to one application, there is no way you can avoid this.) 
\par \pard\plain\f0

