\par \b Standard Streams\b0 
\par 
\par When the \f3 main\f0  function of your program is invoked, it already has three predefined streams open and available for use. These represent the "standard" input and output channels that have been established for the process. 
\par 
\par These streams are declared in the header file \f3 stdio.h\f0 .
\par 
\par -- Variable: FILE * \b stdin\b0 
\par 
\par \pard\li500 The \i standard input\i0  stream, which is the normal source of input for the program.
\par 
\par \pard -- Variable: FILE * \b stdout\b0 
\par 
\par \pard\li500 The \i standard output\i0  stream, which is used for normal output from the program.
\par 
\par \pard -- Variable: FILE * \b stderr\b0 
\par 
\par \pard\li500 The \i standard error\i0  stream, which is used for error messages and diagnostics issued by the program.
\par 
\par \pard In th\f1 is\f0  system, you can specify what files or processes correspond to these streams using the pipe and redirection facilities provided by the shell. (The primitives shells use to implement these facilities are described in  File System Interface .) Most other operating systems provide similar mechanisms, but the details of how to use them can vary. 
\par 
\par In the\f1  \f0 C library, \f3 stdin\f0 , \f3 stdout\f0 , and \f3 stderr\f0  are normal variables which you can set just like any others. For example, to redirect the standard output to a file, you could do:
\par 
\par \f3      fclose (stdout);
\par      stdout = fopen ("standard-output-file", "w");
\par \f0 
\par Note however, that in other systems \f3 stdin\f0 , \f3 stdout\f0 , and\f3  stderr\f0  are macros that you cannot assign to in the normal way. But you can use \f3 freopen\f0  to get the effect of closing one and reopening it. See  Opening Streams . 
\par 
\par The three streams \f3 stdin\f0 , \f3 stdout\f0 , and \f3 stderr\f0  are not unoriented at program start (see  Streams and I18N ).
\par 
\par \pard\plain\f0

