\par \b Streams\b0 
\par 
\par For historical reasons, the type of the C data structure that represents a stream is called \f3 FILE\f0  rather than "stream". Since most of the library functions deal with objects of type \f3 FILE *\f0 , sometimes the term \i file pointer\i0  is also used to mean "stream". This leads to unfortunate confusion over terminology in many books on C. This manual, however, is careful to use the terms "file" and "stream" only in the technical sense. The \f3 FILE\f0  type is declared in the header file \f3 stdio.h\f0 .
\par 
\par -- Data Type: \b FILE\b0 
\par 
\par \pard\li500 This is the data type used to represent stream objects. A \f3 FILE\f0  object holds all of the internal state information about the connection to the associated file, including such things as the file position indicator and buffering information. Each stream also has error and end-of-file status indicators that can be tested with the \f3 ferror\f0  and \f3 feof\f0  functions; see  EOF and Errors .
\par 
\par \pard\f3 FILE\f0  objects are allocated and managed internally by the input/output library functions. Don't try to create your own objects of type \f3 FILE\f0 ; let the library do it. Your programs should deal only with pointers to these objects (that is, \f3 FILE *\f0  values) rather than the objects themselves.
\par 
\par \pard\plain\f0

