\par \b String and Array Utilities\b0 
\par 
\par Operations on strings (or arrays of characters) are an important part of many programs. The C library provides an extensive set of string utility functions, including functions for copying, concatenating, comparing, and searching strings. Many of these functions can also operate on arbitrary regions of storage; for example, the \f3 memcpy\f0  function can be used to copy the contents of any kind of array. 
\par 
\par It's fairly common for beginning C programmers to "reinvent the wheel" by duplicating this functionality in their own code, but it pays to become familiar with the library functions and to make use of them, since this offers benefits in maintenance, efficiency, and portability. 
\par 
\par For instance, you could easily compare one string to another in two lines of C code, but if you use the built-in \f3 strcmp\f0  function, you're less likely to make a mistake. And, since these library functions are typically highly optimized, your program may run faster too.
