\par \b String Input Conversions\b0 
\par 
\par This section describes the \f3 scanf\f0  input conversions for reading string and character values: `\f3 %s\f0 ', `\f3 %S\f0 ', `\f3 %[\f0 ', `\f3 %c\f0 ', and `\f3 %C\f0 '. 
\par 
\par You have two options for how to receive the input from these conversions:
\par 
\par \pard\li500\f2\'b7\f0  Provide a buffer to store it in. This is the default. You should provide an argument of type \f3 char *\f0  or \f3 wchar_t *\f0  (the latter of the `\f3 l\f0 ' modifier is present). 
\par 
\par \b Warning:\b0  To make a robust program, you must make sure that the input (plus its terminating null) cannot possibly exceed the size of the buffer you provide. In general, the only way to do this is to specify a maximum field width one less than the buffer size. \b If you provide the buffer, always specify a maximum field width to prevent overflow.\b0  
\par \f2\'b7\f0  Ask \f3 scanf\f0  to allocate a big enough buffer, by specifying the `\f3 a\f0 ' flag character. This is a GNU extension. You should provide an argument of type \f3 char **\f0  for the buffer address to be stored in. See  Dynamic String Input .
\par 
\par \pard The `\f3 %c\f0 ' conversion is the simplest: it matches a fixed number of characters, always. The maximum field width says how many characters to read; if you don't specify the maximum, the default is 1. This conversion doesn't append a null character to the end of the text it reads. It also does not skip over initial whitespace characters. It reads precisely the next \i n\i0  characters, and fails if it cannot get that many. Since there is always a maximum field width with `\f3 %c\f0 ' (whether specified, or 1 by default), you can always prevent overflow by making the buffer long enough. 
\par 
\par If the format is `\f3 %lc\f0 ' or `\f3 %C\f0 ' the function stores wide characters which are converted using the conversion determined at the time the stream was opened from the external byte stream. The number of bytes read from the medium is limited by \f3 MB_CUR_LEN * \i\f0 n\i0  but at most \i n\i0  wide character get stored in the output string. 
\par 
\par The `\f3 %s\f0 ' conversion matches a string of non-whitespace characters. It skips and discards initial whitespace, but stops when it encounters more whitespace after having read something. It stores a null character at the end of the text that it reads. 
\par 
\par For example, reading the input:
\par 
\par \f3       hello, world
\par \f0 
\par with the conversion `\f3 %10c\f0 ' produces \f3 " hello, wo"\f0 , but reading the same input with the conversion `\f3 %10s\f0 ' produces\f3  "hello,"\f0 . 
\par 
\par \b Warning:\b0  If you do not specify a field width for `\f3 %s\f0 ', then the number of characters read is limited only by where the next whitespace character appears. This almost certainly means that invalid input can make your program crash--which is a bug. 
\par 
\par The `\f3 %ls\f0 ' and `\f3 %S\f0 ' format are handled just like `\f3 %s\f0 ' except that the external byte sequence is converted using the conversion associated with the stream to wide characters with their own encoding. A width or precision specified with the format do not directly determine how many bytes are read from the stream since they measure wide characters. But an upper limit can be computed by multiplying the value of the width or precision by \f3 MB_CUR_MAX\f0 . 
\par 
\par To read in characters that belong to an arbitrary set of your choice, use the `\f3 %[\f0 ' conversion. You specify the set between the `\f3 [\f0 ' character and a following `\f3 ]\f0 ' character, using the same syntax used in regular expressions. As special cases:
\par 
\par \pard\li500\f2\'b7\f0  A literal `\f3 ]\f0 ' character can be specified as the first character of the set. 
\par \f2\'b7\f0  An embedded `\f3 -\f0 ' character (that is, one that is not the first or last character of the set) is used to specify a range of characters. 
\par \f2\'b7\f0  If a caret character `\f3 ^\f0 ' immediately follows the initial `\f3 [\f0 ', then the set of allowed input characters is the everything \i except\i0  the characters listed.
\par 
\par \pard The `\f3 %[\f0 ' conversion does not skip over initial whitespace characters. 
\par 
\par Here are some examples of `\f3 %[\f0 ' conversions and what they mean:
\par 
\par `\f3 %25[1234567890]\f0 '
\par \pard\li500 Matches a string of up to 25 digits. 
\par \pard `\f3 %25[][]\f0 '
\par \pard\li500 Matches a string of up to 25 square brackets. 
\par \pard `\f3 %25[^ \\f\\n\\r\\t'
\par \pard\li500 Matches a string up to 25 characters long that doesn't contain any of the standard whitespace characters. This is slightly different from `%s', because if the input begins with a whitespace character, `%[' reports a matching failure while `%s' simply discards the initial whitespace. 
\par \pard `%25[a-z]'
\par \pard\li500 Matches up to 25 lowercase characters.
\par 
\par \pard As for `%c' and `%s' the `%[' format is also modified to produce wide characters if the `l' modifier is present. All what is said about `%ls' above is true for `%l['. 
\par 
\par One more reminder: the `%s' and `%[' conversions are\b  dangerous\b0  if you don't specify a maximum width or use the `a' flag, because input too long would overflow whatever buffer you have provided for it. No matter how long your buffer is, a user could supply input that is longer. A well-written program reports invalid input with a comprehensible error message, not with a crash.
\par 
\par \f0 
\par \pard\plain\f0

