\par \b Table of Input Conversions\b0 
\par 
\par Here is a table that summarizes the various conversion specifications:
\par 
\par `\f3 %d\f0 '
\par \pard\li500 Matches an optionally signed integer written in decimal. See  Numeric Input Conversions . 
\par \pard `\f3 %i\f0 '
\par \pard\li500 Matches an optionally signed integer in any of the formats that the C language defines for specifying an integer constant. See  Numeric Input Conversions . 
\par \pard `\f3 %o\f0 '
\par \pard\li500 Matches an unsigned integer written in octal radix. See  Numeric Input Conversions . 
\par \pard `\f3 %u\f0 '
\par \pard\li500 Matches an unsigned integer written in decimal radix. See  Numeric Input Conversions . 
\par \pard `\f3 %x\f0 ', `\f3 %X\f0 '
\par \pard\li500 Matches an unsigned integer written in hexadecimal radix. See  Numeric Input Conversions . 
\par \pard `\f3 %e\f0 ', `\f3 %f\f0 ', `\f3 %g\f0 ', `\f3 %E\f0 ', `\f3 %G\f0 '
\par \pard\li500 Matches an optionally signed floating-point number. See  Numeric Input Conversions . 
\par \pard `\f3 %s\f0 '
\par \pard\li500 Matches a string containing only non-whitespace characters. See  String Input Conversions . The presence of the `\f3 l\f0 ' modifier determines whether the output is stored as a wide character string or a multibyte string. If `\f3 %s\f0 ' is used in a wide character function the string is converted as with multiple calls to \f3 wcrtomb\f0  into a multibyte string. This means that the buffer must provide room for\f3  MB_CUR_MAX\f0  bytes for each wide character read. In case `\f3 %ls\f0 ' is used in a multibyte function the result is converted into wide characters as with multiple calls of \f3 mbrtowc\f0  before being stored in the user provided buffer. 
\par \pard `\f3 %S\f0 '
\par \pard\li500 This is an alias for `\f3 %ls\f0 ' which is supported for compatibility with the Unix standard. 
\par \pard `\f3 %[\f0 '
\par \pard\li500 Matches a string of characters that belong to a specified set. See  String Input Conversions . The presence of the `\f3 l\f0 ' modifier determines whether the output is stored as a wide character string or a multibyte string. If `\f3 %[\f0 ' is used in a wide character function the string is converted as with multiple calls to \f3 wcrtomb\f0  into a multibyte string. This means that the buffer must provide room for\f3  MB_CUR_MAX\f0  bytes for each wide character read. In case `\f3 %l[\f0 ' is used in a multibyte function the result is converted into wide characters as with multiple calls of \f3 mbrtowc\f0  before being stored in the user provided buffer. 
\par \pard `\f3 %c\f0 '
\par \pard\li500 Matches a string of one or more characters; the number of characters read is controlled by the maximum field width given for the conversion. See  String Input Conversions . 
\par 
\par If the `\f3 %c\f0 ' is used in a wide stream function the read value is converted from a wide character to the corresponding multibyte character before storing it. Note that this conversion can produce more than one byte of output and therefore the provided buffer be large enough for up to \f3 MB_CUR_MAX\f0  bytes for each character. If `\f3 %lc\f0 ' is used in a multibyte function the input is treated as a multibyte sequence (and not bytes) and the result is converted as with calls to \f3 mbrtowc\f0 . 
\par \pard `\f3 %C\f0 '
\par \pard\li500 This is an alias for `\f3 %lc\f0 ' which is supported for compatibility with the Unix standard. 
\par \pard `\f3 %p\f0 '
\par \pard\li500 Matches a pointer value in the same implementation-defined format used by the `\f3 %p\f0 ' output conversion for \f3 printf\f0 . See  Other Input Conversions . 
\par \pard `\f3 %n\f0 '
\par \pard\li500 This conversion doesn't read any characters; it records the number of characters read so far by this call. See  Other Input Conversions . 
\par \pard `\f3 %%\f0 '
\par \pard\li500 This matches a literal `\f3 %\f0 ' character in the input stream. No corresponding argument is used. See  Other Input Conversions .
\par 
\par \pard If the syntax of a conversion specification is invalid, the behavior is undefined. If there aren't enough function arguments provided to supply addresses for all the conversion specifications in the template strings that perform assignments, or if the arguments are not of the correct types, the behavior is also undefined. On the other hand, extra arguments are simply ignored.
\par 
\par \pard\plain\f0

