\par \pard `\f3 %g\f0 ', `\f3 %G\f0 '
\par \pard\li500 Print a floating-point number in either normal or exponential notation, whichever is more appropriate for its magnitude. `\f3 %g\f0 ' uses lower-case letters and `\f3 %G\f0 ' uses upper-case. See  Floating-Point Conversions , for details. 
\par \pard `\f3 %a\f0 ', `\f3 %A\f0 '
\par \pard\li500 Print a floating-point number in a hexadecimal fractional notation which the exponent to base 2 represented in decimal digits. `\f3 %a\f0 ' uses lower-case letters and `\f3 %A\f0 ' uses upper-case. See  Floating-Point Conversions , for details. 
\par \pard `\f3 %c\f0 '
\par \pard\li500 Print a single character. See  Other Output Conversions . 
\par \pard `\f3 %C\f0 '
\par \pard\li500 This is an alias for `\f3 %lc\f0 ' which is supported for compatibility with the Unix standard. 
\par \pard `\f3 %s\f0 '
\par \pard\li500 Print a string. See  Other Output Conversions . 
\par \pard `\f3 %S\f0 '
\par \pard\li500 This is an alias for `\f3 %ls\f0 ' which is supported for compatibility with the Unix standard. 
\par \pard `\f3 %p\f0 '
\par \pard\li500 Print the value of a pointer. See  Other Output Conversions . 
\par \pard `\f3 %n\f0 '
\par \pard\li500 Get the number of characters printed so far. See  Other Output Conversions . Note that this conversion specification never produces any output. 
\par \pard `\f3 %m\f0 '
\par \pard\li500 Print the string corresponding to the value of \f3 errno\f0 . (This is a GNU extension.) See  Other Output Conversions . 
\par \pard `\f3 %%\f0 '
\par \pard\li500 Print a literal `\f3 %\f0 ' character. See  Other Output Conversions .
\par 
\par \pard If the syntax of a conversion specification is invalid, unpredictable things will happen, so don't do this. If there aren't enough function arguments provided to supply values for all the conversion specifications in the template string, or if the arguments are not of the correct types, the results are unpredictable. If you supply more arguments than conversion specifications, the extra argument values are simply ignored; this is sometimes useful.
