\par \b Notes on using the wide character classes\b0 
\par 
\par The first note is probably not astonishing but still occasionally a cause of problems. The \f3 isw\i\f0 XXX\i0  functions can be implemented using macros and in fact, the \f1 C\f0  C library does this. They are still available as real functions but when the \f3 wctype.h\f0  header is included the macros will be used. This is the same as the\f3  char\f0  type versions of these functions. 
\par 
\par The second note covers something new. It can be best illustrated by a (real-world) example. The first piece of code is an excerpt from the original code. It is truncated a bit but the intention should be clear.
\par 
\par \f3      int
\par      is_in_class (int c, const char *class)
\par      \{
\par        if (strcmp (class, "alnum") == 0)
\par          return isalnum (c);
\par        if (strcmp (class, "alpha") == 0)
\par          return isalpha (c);
\par        if (strcmp (class, "cntrl") == 0)
\par          return iscntrl (c);
\par        ...
\par        return 0;
\par      \}
\par \f0 
\par Now, with the \f3 wctype\f0  and \f3 iswctype\f0  you can avoid the\f3  if\f0  cascades, but rewriting the code as follows is wrong:
\par 
\par \f3      int
\par      is_in_class (int c, const char *class)
\par      \{
\par        wctype_t desc = wctype (class);
\par        return desc ? iswctype ((wint_t) c, desc) : 0;
\par      \}
\par \f0 
\par The problem is that it is not guaranteed that the wide character representation of a single-byte character can be found using casting. In fact, usually this fails miserably. The correct solution to this problem is to write the code as follows:
\par 
\par \f3      int
\par      is_in_class (int c, const char *class)
\par      \{
\par        wctype_t desc = wctype (class);
\par        return desc ? iswctype (btowc (c), desc) : 0;
\par      \}
\par \f0 
\par See  Converting a Character , for more information on \f3 btowc\f0 . Note that this change probably does not improve the performance of the program a lot since the \f3 wctype\f0  function still has to make the string comparisons. It gets really interesting if the\f3  is_in_class\f0  function is called more than once for the same class name. In this case the variable \i desc\i0  could be computed once and reused for all the calls. Therefore the above form of the function is probably not the final one.
\par 
\par \pard\plain\f0

