\par \b Variable Arguments Output Functions\b0 
\par 
\par The functions \f3 vprintf\f0  and friends are provided so that you can define your own variadic \f3 printf\f0 -like functions that make use of the same internals as the built-in formatted output functions. 
\par 
\par The most natural way to define such functions would be to use a language construct to say, "Call \f3 printf\f0  and pass this template plus all of my arguments after the first five." But there is no way to do this in C, and it would be hard to provide a way, since at the C language level there is no way to tell how many arguments your function received. 
\par 
\par Since that method is impossible, we provide alternative functions, the\f3  vprintf\f0  series, which lets you pass a \f3 va_list\f0  to describe "all of my arguments after the first five." 
\par 
\par When it is sufficient to define a macro rather than a real function, \f1 C99\f0  provides a way to do this much more easily with macros. For example:
\par 
\par \f3      #define myprintf(a, b, c, d, e, rest...) \\
\par                  printf (mytemplate , ## rest...)
\par \f0 
\par But this is limited to macros, and does not apply to real functions at all. 
\par 
\par Before calling \f3 vprintf\f0  or the other functions listed in this section, you \i must\i0  call \f3 va_start\f0  (see  Variadic Functions ) to initialize a pointer to the variable arguments. Then you can call \f3 va_arg\f0  to fetch the arguments that you want to handle yourself. This advances the pointer past those arguments. 
\par 
\par Once your \f3 va_list\f0  pointer is pointing at the argument of your choice, you are ready to call \f3 vprintf\f0 . That argument and all subsequent arguments that were passed to your function are used by\f3  vprintf\f0  along with the template that you specified separately. 
\par 
\par In some other systems, the \f3 va_list\f0  pointer may become invalid after the call to \f3 vprintf\f0 , so you must not use \f3 va_arg\f0  after you call \f3 vprintf\f0 . Instead, you should call \f3 va_end\f0  to retire the pointer from service. However, you can safely call\f3  va_start\f0  on another pointer variable and begin fetching the arguments again through that pointer. Calling \f3 vprintf\f0  does not destroy the argument list of your function, merely the particular pointer that you passed to it. 
\par 
\par \f1 CC386\f0  does not have such restrictions. You can safely continue to fetch arguments from a \f3 va_list\f0  pointer after passing it to\f3  vprintf\f0 , and \f3 va_end\f0  is a no-op. (Note, however, that subsequent \f3 va_arg\f0  calls will fetch the same arguments which\f3  vprintf\f0  previously used.) 
\par 
\par Prototypes for these functions are declared in \f3 stdio.h\f0 .
\par 
\par -- Function: int \b vprintf\b0  (\i const char *template, va_list ap\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 This function is similar to \f3 printf\f0  except that, instead of taking a variable number of arguments directly, it takes an argument list pointer \i ap\i0 .
\par 
\par \pard -- Function: int \b vwprintf\b0  (\i const wchar_t *template, va_list ap\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 This function is similar to \f3 wprintf\f0  except that, instead of taking a variable number of arguments directly, it takes an argument list pointer \i ap\i0 .
\par 
\par \pard -- Function: int \b vfprintf\b0  (\i FILE *stream, const char *template, va_list ap\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 This is the equivalent of \f3 fprintf\f0  with the variable argument list specified directly as for \f3 vprintf\f0 .
\par 
\par \pard -- Function: int \b vfwprintf\b0  (\i FILE *stream, const wchar_t *template, va_list ap\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 This is the equivalent of \f3 fwprintf\f0  with the variable argument list specified directly as for \f3 vwprintf\f0 .
\par 
\par \pard -- Function: int \b vsprintf\b0  (\i char *s, const char *template, va_list ap\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 This is the equivalent of \f3 sprintf\f0  with the variable argument list specified directly as for \f3 vprintf\f0 .
\par 
\par \pard -- Function: int \b vswprintf\b0  (\i wchar_t *s, size_t size, const wchar_t *template, va_list ap\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 This is the equivalent of \f3 swprintf\f0  with the variable argument list specified directly as for \f3 vwprintf\f0 .
\par 
\par \pard -- Function: int \b vsnprintf\b0  (\i char *s, size_t size, const char *template, va_list ap\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 This is the equivalent of \f3 snprintf\f0  with the variable argument list specified directly as for \f3 vprintf\f0 .
\par 
\par \pard -- Function: int \b vasprintf\b0  (\i char **ptr, const char *template, va_list ap\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 The \f3 vasprintf\f0  function is the equivalent of \f3 asprintf\f0  with the variable argument list specified directly as for \f3 vprintf\f0 .
\par 
\par \pard -- Function: int \b obstack_vprintf\b0  (\i struct obstack *obstack, const char *template, va_list ap\i0 )
\par 
\par \pard\li500 The \f3 obstack_vprintf\f0  function is the equivalent of\f3  obstack_printf\f0  with the variable argument list specified directly as for \f3 vprintf\f0 .
\par 
\par \pard Here's an example showing how you might use \f3 vfprintf\f0 . This is a function that prints error messages to the stream \f3 stderr\f0 , along with a prefix indicating the name of the program (see  Error Messages , for a description of\f3  program_invocation_short_name\f0 ).
\par 
\par \f3      #include <stdio.h>
\par      #include <stdarg.h>
\par      
\par      void
\par      eprintf (const char *template, ...)
\par      \{
\par        va_list ap;
\par        extern char *program_invocation_short_name;
\par      
\par        fprintf (stderr, "%s: ", program_invocation_short_name);
\par        va_start (ap, template);
\par        vfprintf (stderr, template, ap);
\par        va_end (ap);
\par      \}
\par \f0 
\par You could call \f3 eprintf\f0  like this:
\par 
\par \f3      eprintf ("file `%s' does not exist\\n", filename);
\par \f0 
