\viewkind4\uc1\pard\qc\lang1033\f0\fs24 Width of\f1  \f0 Type 
\par \pard\fs18 Next:  Range of Type , Up:  Data Type Measurements 
\par \fs10 
\par \pard\ri100\fs2 
\par \pard\fs10 
\par \fs18 
\par \b Computing the Width of an Integer Data Type\b0 
\par 
\par The most common reason that a program needs to know how many bits are in an integer type is for using an array of \f3 long int\f0  as a bit vector. You can access the bit at index \i n\i0  with
\par 
\par \f3      vector[\i n\i0  / LONGBITS] & (1 << (\i n\i0  % LONGBITS))
\par \f0 
\par provided you define \f3 LONGBITS\f0  as the number of bits in a\f3  long int\f0 . 
\par 
\par There is no operator in the C language that can give you the number of bits in an integer data type. But you can compute it from the macro\f3  CHAR_BIT\f0 , defined in the header file \f3 limits.h\f0 .
\par 
\par \f3 CHAR_BIT\f0 
\par \pard\li500 This is the number of bits in a \f3 char\f0 --eight, on most systems. The value has type \f3 int\f0 . 
\par 
\par You can compute the number of bits in any data type \i type\i0  like this: 
\par 
\par \f3           sizeof (\i type\i0 ) * CHAR_BIT
\par      
\par \pard\plain\f0

